# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blockchain-mining
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] An **application-specific integrated circuit** (**ASIC** /ˈeɪsɪk/) is an integrated circuit (IC) chip customized for a particular use, rather than intended for general-purpose use, such as a chip designed to run in a digital voice recorder or a high-efficiency video codec.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Application-specific standard product chips are intermediate between ASICs and industry standard integrated circuits like the 7400 series or the 4000 series.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASIC chips are typically fabricated using metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, as MOS integrated circuit chips.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] As feature sizes have shrunk and chip design tools improved over the years, the maximum complexity (and hence functionality) possible in an ASIC has grown from 5,000 logic gates to over 100 million.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Modern ASICs often include entire microprocessors, memory blocks including ROM, RAM, EEPROM, flash memory and other large building blocks.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Such an ASIC is often termed a SoC (system-on-chip).
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Designers of digital ASICs often use a hardware description language (HDL), such as Verilog or VHDL, to describe the functionality of ASICs.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Field-programmable gate arrays (FPGA) are the modern-day technology improvement on breadboards, meaning that they are not made to be application-specific as opposed to ASICs.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Programmable logic blocks and programmable interconnects allow the same FPGA to be used in many different applications.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For smaller designs or lower production volumes, FPGAs may be more cost-effective than an ASIC design, even in production.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The non-recurring engineering (NRE) cost of an ASIC can run into the millions of dollars.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Therefore, device manufacturers typically prefer FPGAs for prototyping and devices with low production volume and ASICs for very large production volumes where NRE costs can be amortized across many devices.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By 1967, Ferranti and Interdesign were manufacturing early bipolar gate arrays.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In 1967, Fairchild Semiconductor introduced the Micromatrix family of bipolar diode–transistor logic (DTL) and transistor–transistor logic (TTL) arrays.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) technology opened the door to the broad commercialization of gate arrays.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The first CMOS gate arrays were developed by Robert Lipp, in 1974 for International Microcircuits, Inc.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) standard-cell technology was introduced by Fairchild and Motorola, under the trade names Micromosaic and Polycell, in the 1970s.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This technology was later successfully commercialized by VLSI Technology (founded 1979) and LSI Logic (1981).
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] A successful commercial application of gate array circuitry was found in the low-end 8-bit ZX81 and ZX Spectrum personal computers, introduced in 1981 and 1982.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These were used by Sinclair Research (UK) essentially as a low-cost I/O solution aimed at handling the computer's graphics.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Customization occurred by varying a metal interconnect mask.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate arrays had complexities of up to a few thousand gates; this is now called mid-scale integration.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Later versions became more generalized, with different base dies customized by both metal and polysilicon layers.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Some base dies also include random-access memory (RAM) elements.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In the mid-1980s, a designer would choose an ASIC manufacturer and implement their design using the design tools available from the manufacturer.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] While third-party design tools were available, there was not an effective link from the third-party design tools to the layout and actual semiconductor process performance characteristics of the various ASIC manufacturers.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Most designers used factory-specific tools to complete the implementation of their designs.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] A solution to this problem, which also yielded a much higher density device, was the implementation of standard cells.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Every ASIC manufacturer could create functional blocks with known electrical characteristics, such as propagation delay, capacitance and inductance, that could also be represented in third-party tools.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard-cell design is the utilization of these functional blocks to achieve very high gate density and good electrical performance.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard-cell design is intermediate between § Gate-array and semi-custom design and § Full-custom design in terms of its non-recurring engineering and recurring component costs as well as performance and speed of development (including time to market).
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By the late 1990s, logic synthesis tools became available.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Such tools could compile HDL descriptions into a gate-level netlist.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Register-transfer level (RTL) design**: The design team constructs a description of an ASIC to achieve these goals using a hardware description language.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This process is similar to writing a computer program in a high-level language.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Functional verification**: Suitability for purpose is verified by functional verification.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This may include such techniques as logic simulation through test benches, formal verification, emulation, or creating and evaluating an equivalent pure software model, as in Simics.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Each verification technique has advantages and disadvantages, and most often several methods are used together for ASIC verification.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Unlike most FPGAs, ASICs cannot be reprogrammed once fabricated and therefore ASIC designs that are not completely correct are much more costly, increasing the need for full test coverage.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Logic synthesis**: Logic synthesis transforms the RTL design into a large collection called of lower-level constructs called standard cells.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These constructs are taken from a standard-cell library consisting of pre-characterized collections of logic gates performing specific functions.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The standard cells are typically specific to the planned manufacturer of the ASIC.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The resulting collection of standard cells and the needed electrical connections between them is called a gate-level netlist.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Placement**: The gate-level netlist is next processed by a placement tool which places the standard cells onto a region of an integrated circuit die representing the final ASIC.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The placement tool attempts to find an optimized placement of the standard cells, subject to a variety of specified constraints.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Routing**: An electronics routing tool takes the physical placement of the standard cells and uses the netlist to create the electrical connections between them.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Since the search space is large, this process will produce a "sufficient" rather than "globally optimal" solution.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The output is a file which can be used to create a set of photomasks enabling a semiconductor fabrication facility, commonly called a "fab" or "foundry" to manufacture physical integrated circuits.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Placement and routing are closely interrelated and are collectively called place and route in electronics design.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] While Logic synthesis, Placement, and Routing are supported by electronic design automation tools, these stages require significant designer guidance and iteration.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Designers provide constraints derived from requirements engineering and RTL design, including timing requirements, floorplans, power budgets, and area restrictions.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Multiple tool iterations are typically necessary to meet performance, power, and area objectives, often requiring manual optimization and refinement that extends design cycle time considerably.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Sign-off**: Given the final layout, circuit extraction computes the parasitic resistances and capacitances.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In the case of a digital circuit, this will then be further mapped into delay information from which the circuit performance can be estimated, usually by static timing analysis.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This, and other final tests such as design rule checking and power analysis collectively called signoff are intended to ensure that the device will function correctly over all extremes of the process, voltage and temperature.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] When this testing is complete the photomask information is released for chip fabrication.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These steps, implemented with a level of skill common in the industry, almost always produce a final device that correctly implements the original design, unless flaws are later introduced by the physical fabrication process.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The design steps also called design flow, are common to standard product design.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The significant difference is that standard-cell design uses the manufacturer's cell libraries that have been used in potentially hundreds of other design implementations and therefore are of much lower risk than a full custom design.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard cells produce a design density that is cost-effective, and they can also integrate IP cores and static random-access memory (SRAM) effectively, unlike gate arrays.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate array design is a manufacturing method in which diffused layers, each consisting of transistors and other active devices, are predefined and electronics wafers containing such devices are "held in stock" or unconnected prior to the metallization stage of the fabrication process.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The physical design process defines the interconnections of these layers for the final device.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For most ASIC manufacturers, this consists of between two and nine metal layers with each layer running perpendicular to the one below it.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Non-recurring engineering costs are much lower than full custom designs, as photolithographic masks are required only for the metal layers.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Production cycles are much shorter, as metallization is a comparatively quick process; thereby accelerating time to market.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate-array ASICs are always a compromise between rapid design and performance as mapping a given design onto what a manufacturer held as a stock wafer never gives 100% circuit utilization.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Often difficulties in routing the interconnect require migration onto a larger array device with a consequent increase in the piece part price.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These difficulties are often a result of the layout EDA software used to develop the interconnect.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Pure, logic-only gate-array design is rarely implemented by circuit designers today, having been almost entirely replaced by field-programmable devices.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The most prominent of such devices are field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) which can be programmed by the user and thus offer minimal tooling charges, non-recurring engineering, only marginally increased piece part cost, and comparable performance.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Today, gate arrays are evolving into structured ASICs that consist of a large IP core like a CPU, digital signal processor units, peripherals, standard interfaces, integrated memories, SRAM, and a block of reconfigurable, uncommitted logic.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In their frequent usages in the field, the terms "gate array" and "semi-custom" are synonymous when referring to ASICs.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Process engineers more commonly use the term "semi-custom", while "gate-array" is more commonly used by logic (or gate-level) designers.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By contrast, full-custom ASIC design defines all the photolithographic layers of the device.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Full-custom design is used for both ASIC design and for standard product design.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The benefits of full-custom design include reduced area (and therefore recurring component cost), performance improvements, and also the ability to integrate analog components and other pre-designed—and thus fully verified—components, such as microprocessor cores, that form a system on a chip.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The disadvantages of full-custom design can include increased manufacturing and design time, increased non-recurring engineering costs, more complexity in the computer-aided design (CAD) and electronic design automation systems, and a much higher skill requirement on the part of the design team.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For digital-only designs, however, "standard-cell" cell libraries, together with modern CAD systems, can offer considerable performance/cost benefits with low risk.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Automated layout tools are quick and easy to use and also offer the possibility to "hand-tweak" or manually optimize any performance-limiting aspect of the design.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This is designed by using basic logic gates, circuits or layout specially for a design.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This is effectively the same definition as a gate array.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] What distinguishes a structured ASIC from a gate array is that in a gate array, the predefined metal layers serve to make manufacturing turnaround faster.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In a structured ASIC, the use of predefined metallization is primarily to reduce cost of the mask sets as well as making the design cycle time significantly shorter.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For example, in a cell-based or gate-array design the user must often design power, clock, and test structures themselves.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By contrast, these are predefined in most structured ASICs and therefore can save time and expense for the designer compared to gate-array based designs.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Likewise, the design tools used for structured ASIC can be substantially lower cost and easier (faster) to use than cell-based tools, because they do not have to perform all the functions that cell-based tools do.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In some cases, the structured ASIC vendor requires customized tools for their device (e.g., custom physical synthesis) be used, also allowing for the design to be brought into manufacturing more quickly.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Cell libraries of logical primitives are usually provided by the device manufacturer as part of the service.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Although they will incur no additional cost, their release will be covered by the terms of a non-disclosure agreement (NDA) and they will be regarded as intellectual property by the manufacturer.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Usually, their physical design will be pre-defined so they could be termed "hard macros".
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] What most engineers understand as "intellectual property" are IP cores, designs purchased from a third-party as sub-components of a larger ASIC.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] They may be provided in the form of a hardware description language (often termed a "soft macro"), or as a fully routed design that could be printed directly onto an ASIC's mask (often termed a "hard macro").
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Many organizations now sell such pre-designed cores – CPUs, Ethernet, USB or telephone interfaces – and larger organizations may have an entire department or division to produce cores for the rest of the organization.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The company ARM *only* sells IP cores, making it a fabless manufacturer.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Additionally, open-source hardware organizations such as OpenCores are collecting free IP cores, paralleling the open-source software movement in hardware design.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Soft macros are often process-independent (i.e. they can be fabricated on a wide range of manufacturing processes and different manufacturers).
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Hard macros are process-limited and usually further design effort must be invested to migrate (port) to a different process or manufacturer.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Some manufacturers and IC design houses offer multi-project wafer service (MPW) as a method of obtaining low cost prototypes.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Often called shuttles, these MPWs, containing several designs, run at regular, scheduled intervals on a "cut and go" basis, usually with limited liability on the part of the manufacturer.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The contract involves delivery of bare dies or the assembly and packaging of a handful of devices.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The service usually involves the supply of a physical design database (i.e. masking information or pattern generation (PG) tape).
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The manufacturer is often referred to as a "silicon foundry" due to the low involvement it has in the process.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] An **application-specific standard product** (**ASSP**) is an integrated circuit that implements a specific function that appeals to a wide market.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] As opposed to ASICs that combine a collection of functions and are designed by or for one customer, ASSPs are available as off-the-shelf components.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASSPs are used in all industries, from automotive to communications.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For example, two ICs that might or might not be considered ASICs are a controller chip for a PC and a chip for a modem.
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Both of these examples are specific to an application (which is typical of an ASIC) but are sold to many different system vendors (which is typical of standard parts).
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASICs such as these are sometimes called application-specific standard products (ASSPs).
[src:blockchain-mining/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Examples of ASSPs are encoding/decoding chip, Ethernet network interface controller chip and flash memory controller chip.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin works through the collaboration of computers, each of which acts as a node in the peer-to-peer bitcoin network.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Each node maintains an independent copy of a public distributed ledger of transactions, called a blockchain, without central oversight.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Transactions are validated through the use of cryptography, preventing one person from spending another person's bitcoin, as long as the owner of the bitcoin keeps certain sensitive data secret.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Consensus between nodes about the content of the blockchain is achieved using a computationally intensive process based on proof of work, called mining, which is performed by purpose-built computers.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Mining consumes large quantities of electricity, with surveyed miners reporting that 52% of their electricity use came from sustainable energy sources, and has been criticized for its environmental impact.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Before bitcoin, several digital cash technologies were released, starting with David Chaum's ecash in the 1980s.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The idea that solutions to computational puzzles could have some value was first proposed by cryptographers Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor in 1992.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The concept was independently rediscovered by Adam Back who developed Hashcash, a proof-of-work scheme for spam control in 1997.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The first proposals for distributed digital scarcity-based cryptocurrencies came from cypherpunks Wei Dai (b-money) and Nick Szabo (bit gold) in 1998.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In 2004, Hal Finney developed the first currency based on reusable proof of work.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] These various attempts were not successful: Chaum's concept required centralized control and no banks wanted to sign on, Hashcash had no protection against double-spending, while b-money and bit gold were not resistant to Sybil attacks.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The domain name *bitcoin.org* was registered on 18 August 2008.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] On 31 October 2008, a link to a white paper authored by Satoshi Nakamoto titled *Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System* was posted to a cryptography mailing list.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] According to computer scientist Arvind Narayanan, all individual components of bitcoin originated in earlier academic literature.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Nakamoto's innovation was their complex interplay which resulted in the first decentralized, Sybil resistant, Byzantine fault tolerant digital cash system, that would eventually be referred to as the first blockchain.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Nakamoto's paper was not peer-reviewed and was initially ignored by academics, who argued that it could not work.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Nakamoto released bitcoin as open-source software.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] On 3 January 2009, the bitcoin network was created when Nakamoto mined the starting block of the chain, known as the *genesis block*.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Embedded in this block was the text "The Times 03/Jan/2009 Chancellor on brink of second bailout for banks", which is the date and headline of an issue of *The Times* newspaper.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Nine days later, Hal Finney received the first bitcoin transaction: ten bitcoins from Nakamoto.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Wei Dai and Nick Szabo were also early supporters.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] On May 22, 2010, the first known commercial transaction using bitcoin occurred when programmer Laszlo Hanyecz bought two Papa John's pizzas for ₿10,000, in what would later be celebrated as "Bitcoin Pizza Day".
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Satoshi tasked Finnish developer and early Bitcoin contributor Martti Malmi with creating content for the bitcoin.org website.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Blockchain analysts estimate that Nakamoto had mined about one million bitcoins before he disappeared in 2010 and handed the network alert key and control of the code repository over to Gavin Andresen.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Andresen later became lead developer at the Bitcoin Foundation, an organization founded in September 2012 to promote bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] After early "proof-of-concept" transactions, the first major users of bitcoin were black markets, such as the dark web Silk Road.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] During its 30 months of existence, beginning in February 2011, Silk Road exclusively accepted bitcoins as payment, transacting ₿9.9 million, worth about $214 million.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In May 2013, US authorities seized the unregistered exchange Mt.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In June 2013, the US Drug Enforcement Administration seized ₿11.02 from an individual attempting to use them to purchase illicit drugs.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] This marked the first time a government agency had seized bitcoins.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The FBI seized about ₿30,000 in October 2013 from Silk Road, following the arrest of its founder Ross Ulbricht.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In December 2013, the People's Bank of China prohibited Chinese financial institutions from using bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] After the announcement, the value of bitcoin dropped, and Baidu no longer accepted bitcoins for certain services.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Buying real-world goods with any virtual currency had been illegal in China since at least 2009.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Research produced by the University of Cambridge estimated that in 2017, there were 2.9 to 5.8 million unique users using a cryptocurrency wallet, most of them using bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In August 2017, the SegWit software upgrade was activated.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Segwit was intended to support the Lightning Network as well as improve scalability.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] SegWit opponents, who supported larger blocks as a scalability solution, forked to create Bitcoin Cash, one of many forks of bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In December 2017, the first futures on bitcoin was introduced by the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (CME).
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In February 2018, the price crashed after China imposed a complete ban on bitcoin trading.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The percentage of bitcoin trading in the Chinese renminbi fell from over 90% in September 2017 to less than 1% in June 2018.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] During the same year, bitcoin prices were negatively affected by several hacks or thefts from cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In 2020, some major companies and institutions started to acquire bitcoin: MicroStrategy invested $250 million in bitcoin as a treasury reserve asset, Square, Inc., $50 million, and MassMutual, $100 million.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In November 2020, PayPal added support for bitcoin in the US.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In February 2021, bitcoin's market capitalization reached $1 trillion for the first time.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In November 2021, the Taproot soft-fork upgrade was activated, adding support for Schnorr signatures, improved functionality of smart contracts and Lightning Network.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Before, bitcoin only used a custom elliptic curve with the ECDSA algorithm to produce signatures.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In September 2021, bitcoin became legal tender currency in El Salvador, alongside the US dollar.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In October 2021, the first bitcoin futures exchange-traded fund (ETF), called BITO, from ProShares was approved by the SEC and listed on the CME.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In early 2022, during the Canadian trucker protests opposing COVID-19 vaccine mandates, organizers turned to bitcoin to receive donations after traditional financial platforms restricted access to funding.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Proponents highlighted bitcoin's use as a tool for fundraising in situations where access to conventional financial systems may be restricted.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In May and June 2022, the bitcoin price fell following the collapses of TerraUSD, a stablecoin, and the Celsius Network, a cryptocurrency loan company.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In 2023, ordinals—non-fungible tokens (NFTs)—on bitcoin, went live.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As of June 2023, River Financial estimated that bitcoin had 81.7 million users, about 1% of the global population.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In January 2024, the first 11 US spot bitcoin ETFs began trading, offering direct exposure to bitcoin for the first time on American stock exchanges.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In December 2024, bitcoin price reached $100,000 for the first time, as US president-elect Donald Trump promised to make the US the "crypto capital of the planet" and to stockpile bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The same month, BlackRock, the world's largest asset manager, recommended investors to allocate up to 2% of their portfolio to bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As of 2025, the Salvadoran government continues to describe Bitcoin as legal tender under the 2021 Bitcoin Law; however, a January 2025 reform removed obligations for businesses and the government to accept it, so many analysts regard its legal-tender status as effectively ended in practice.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In March 2025, President Trump signed an executive order to establish a strategic bitcoin reserve.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Later that year, some U.S. states, such as Texas and New Hampshire also instituted strategic bitcoin reserves, and the Czech National Bank bought less than €1 million in a "test portfolio".
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin logos made by Satoshi Nakamoto in 2009 (left) and 2010 (right).
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The unit of account of the bitcoin system is the *bitcoin*.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] It is most commonly represented with the symbol ₿ designed in 2010 and the currency code BTC.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] However, the BTC code does not conform to ISO 4217 as BT is the country code of Bhutan, and ISO 4217 requires the first letter used in global commodities to be 'X'.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] XBT, a code that conforms to ISO 4217 though not officially part of it, is used by Bloomberg L.P.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] No uniform capitalization convention exists; some sources use *Bitcoin*, capitalized, to refer to the technology and network, and *bitcoin*, lowercase, for the unit of account.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The *Cambridge Advanced Learner's Dictionary* and the *Oxford Advanced Learner's Dictionary* use the capitalized and lowercase variants without distinction.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] One bitcoin is divisible to eight decimal places.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Units for smaller amounts of bitcoin are the millibitcoin (mBTC), equal to 1⁄1000 bitcoin, and the satoshi (sat), representing 1⁄100000000 (one hundred millionth) bitcoin, the smallest amount possible.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As a decentralized system, bitcoin operates without a central authority or single administrator, so that anyone can create a new bitcoin address and transact without needing any approval.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] This is accomplished through a specialized distributed ledger called a *blockchain* that records bitcoin transactions.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The blockchain is implemented as an ordered list of *blocks*.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Each block contains a SHA-256 hash of the previous block, chaining them in chronological order.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The blockchain is maintained by a peer-to-peer network.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Individual blocks, public addresses, and transactions within blocks are public information, and can be examined using a blockchain explorer.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Nodes validate and broadcast transactions.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Each node maintains a copy of the blockchain for ownership verification.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] A new block is created every 10 minutes on average, updating the blockchain across all nodes without central oversight.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] This process tracks bitcoin spending, ensuring each bitcoin is spent only once.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Unlike a traditional ledger that tracks physical currency, bitcoins exist digitally as unspent outputs of transactions.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In the blockchain, bitcoins are linked to specific strings called addresses.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Most often, an address encodes a hash of a single public key.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Creating such an address involves generating a random private key and then computing the corresponding address.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] This process is almost instant, but the reverse (finding the private key for a given address) is nearly impossible.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Publishing such a bitcoin address does not risk its private key, and it is extremely unlikely to accidentally generate a used key with funds.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] To use bitcoins, owners need their private key to digitally sign transactions, which are verified by the network using the public key, keeping the private key secret.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] An address may encode the hash of a bitcoin script that specifies more complex requirements to spend the funds.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] One common example is "multisig", in which multiple distinct private keys must mutually sign any transaction that attempts to spend the funds.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin transactions use a Forth-like scripting language, involving one or more inputs and outputs.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] When sending bitcoins, a user specifies the recipients' addresses and the amount for each output.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] This allows sending bitcoins to several recipients in a single transaction.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] To prevent double-spending, each input must refer to a previous unspent output in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Using multiple inputs is similar to using multiple coins in a cash transaction.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As in a cash transaction, the sum of inputs can exceed the intended sum of payments.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In such a case, an additional output can return the change back to the payer.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Unallocated input satoshis in the transaction become the transaction fee.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Losing a private key means losing access to the bitcoins, with no other proof of ownership accepted by the protocol.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] For instance, in 2013, a user lost ₿7,500, valued at US$7.5 million, by accidentally discarding a hard drive with the private key.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] It is estimated that around 20% of all bitcoins are lost.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The private key must also be kept secret as its exposure, such as through a data breach, can lead to theft of the associated bitcoins.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As of December 2017, approximately ₿980,000 had been stolen from cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Miners don't directly act as nodes, but do communicate with nodes.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The mining process in bitcoin involves maintaining the blockchain through computer processing power.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Miners group and broadcast new transactions into blocks, which are then verified by the network.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Each block must contain a proof of work (PoW) to be accepted, involving finding a nonce number that, combined with the block content, produces a hash numerically smaller than the network's *difficulty target*.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] This PoW is simple to verify but hard to generate, requiring many attempts.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] PoW forms the basis of bitcoin's consensus mechanism.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The difficulty of generating a block is deterministically adjusted based on the mining power on the network by changing the difficulty target, which is recalibrated every 2,016 blocks (approximately two weeks) to maintain an average time of ten minutes between new blocks.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The process requires significant computational power and specialized hardware.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Miners who successfully create a new block with a valid nonce can collect transaction fees from the included transactions and a fixed reward in bitcoins.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] To claim this reward, a special transaction called a *coinbase* is included in the block, with the miner as the payee.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] All bitcoins in existence have been created through this type of transaction.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] This reward is halved every 210,000 blocks until ₿21 million have been issued in total, which is expected to occur around the year 2140.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Afterward, miners will only earn from transaction fees.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] These fees are determined by the transaction's size and the amount of data stored, measured in satoshis per byte.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The proof of work system and the chaining of blocks make blockchain modifications very difficult, as altering one block requires changing all subsequent blocks.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As more blocks are added, modifying older blocks becomes increasingly challenging.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In case of disagreement, nodes trust the longest chain, which required the greatest amount of effort to produce.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] To tamper or censor the ledger, one needs to control the majority of the global hashrate.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The high cost required to reach this level of computational power secures the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The environmental impact of bitcoin mining is controversial and has attracted the attention of regulators, leading to restrictions or incentives in various jurisdictions.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As of 2025, a non-peer-reviewed study by the Cambridge Centre for Alternative Finance (CCAF) estimated that bitcoin mining represented 0.5% of global electricity consumption and 0.08% of world greenhouse gas emissions, comparable to Slovakia's emissions.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] About half of the electricity used is generated through fossil fuels.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Moreover, mining hardware's short lifespan results in electronic waste.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In October 2025, the US was the largest mining country with 38% of the global bitcoin mining market share, followed by Russia (16%) and China (14%, despite all cryptocurrency trading and mining being banned there in 2021).
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin is pseudonymous, with funds linked to addresses, not real-world identities.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] While the owners of these addresses are not directly identified, all transactions are public on the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Patterns of use, like spending coins from multiple inputs, can hint at a common owner.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Public data can sometimes be matched with known address owners.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin exchanges might also need to collect personal data as per legal requirements.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] For enhanced privacy, users can generate a new address for each transaction.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In the bitcoin network, each bitcoin is treated equally, ensuring basic fungibility.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] However, users and applications can choose to differentiate between bitcoins.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] While wallets and software treat all bitcoins the same, each bitcoin's transaction history is recorded on the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] This public record allows for chain analysis, where users can identify and potentially reject bitcoins from controversial sources.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Gox froze accounts containing bitcoins identified as stolen.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin wallets were the first cryptocurrency wallets, enabling users to store the information necessary to transact bitcoins.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The first wallet program, simply named *Bitcoin*, and sometimes referred to as the *Satoshi client*, was released in 2009 by Nakamoto as open-source software.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin Core is among the best known clients.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Forks of Bitcoin Core exist such as Bitcoin Unlimited.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Wallets can be full clients, with a full copy of the blockchain to check the validity of mined blocks, or lightweight clients, just to send and receive transactions without a local copy of the entire blockchain.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Third-party internet services, called online wallets or hot wallets, store users' credentials on their servers, making them susceptible of hacks.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Cold storage protects bitcoins from such hacks by keeping private keys offline, either through specialized hardware wallets or paper printouts.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Nakamoto limited the block size to one megabyte.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The limited block size and frequency can lead to delayed processing of transactions, increased fees and a bitcoin scalability problem.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The Lightning Network, a second-layer routing network, is a potential scaling solution.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Research shows a trend towards centralization in bitcoin as miners join pools for stable income.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] If a single miner or pool controls more than 50% of the hashing power, it would allow them to censor transactions and double-spend coins.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In 2014, mining pool Ghash.io reached 51% mining power, causing safety concerns, but later voluntarily capped its power at 39.99% for the benefit of the whole network.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] A few entities also dominate other parts of the ecosystem such as the client software, online wallets, and simplified payment verification (SPV) clients.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Sociologist Nigel Dodd argues that the essence of the bitcoin ideology is to remove money from social, as well as governmental, control.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] *The Economist* describes bitcoin as "a techno-anarchist project to create an online version of cash, a way for people to transact without the possibility of interference from malicious governments or banks".
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] These philosophical ideas initially attracted libertarians and anarchists.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Money serves three purposes: a store of value, a medium of exchange, and a unit of account.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] According to *The Economist* in 2014, bitcoin functions best as a medium of exchange.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In 2015, *The Economist* noted that bitcoins had three qualities useful in a currency: they are "hard to earn, limited in supply and easy to verify".
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] However, a 2018 assessment by *The Economist* stated that cryptocurrencies met none of these three criteria.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Per some researchers, as of 2015, bitcoin functions more as a payment system than as a currency.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Shiller wrote that bitcoin has potential as a unit of account for measuring the relative value of goods, as with Chile's Unidad de Fomento, but that "Bitcoin in its present form... doesn't really solve any sensible economic problem".
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The legal status of bitcoin varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Because of its decentralized nature and its global presence, regulating bitcoin is difficult.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] However, the use of bitcoin can be criminalized, and shutting down exchanges and the peer-to-peer economy in a given country would constitute a de facto ban.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The use of bitcoin by criminals has attracted the attention of financial regulators, legislative bodies, and law enforcement.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Nobel-prize winning economist Joseph Stiglitz says that bitcoin's anonymity encourages money laundering and other crimes.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] This is the main justification behind bitcoin bans.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As of November 2021, nine countries applied an absolute ban (Algeria, Bangladesh, China, Egypt, Iraq, Morocco, Nepal, Qatar, and Tunisia) while another 42 countries had an implicit ban.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] According to Harvard Professor Kenneth Rogoff as of 2025, bitcoin is rarely used in regular transactions with merchants, but is popular in the informal economy and for criminal activities.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Prices are not usually quoted in bitcoin and trades involve conversions into fiat currencies.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Commonly cited reasons for not using bitcoin include high costs, the inability to process chargebacks, high price volatility, long transaction times, and transaction fees (especially for small purchases).
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] *Bloomberg* reported that bitcoin was being used for large-item purchases on the site Overstock.com and for cross-border payments to freelancers.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As of 2015, there was little sign of bitcoin use in international remittances despite high fees charged by banks and Western Union.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] From September 2021 until January 2025, the Bitcoin Law made bitcoin a legal tender currency in El Salvador, alongside the US dollar.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The adoption had been criticized internationally and within El Salvador.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In 2022, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) urged El Salvador to reverse its decision.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As of 2022, the use of Bitcoin in El Salvador remained low: 80% of businesses refused to accept it.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In 2025, El Salvador's government revoked bitcoin's status as legal tender currency in order to comply with conditions set by the IMF for a loan.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] El Salvador still describes bitcoin as "legal tender", but its acceptance is no longer obligitory (as it is with the US dollar) and the El Salvador government no longer accepts bitcoin for payment of taxes or fees.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In April 2022, the Central African Republic (CAR) adopted bitcoin as legal tender alongside the CFA franc, but repealed the reform one year later.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin is also used by some governments.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] For instance, the Iranian government initially opposed cryptocurrencies, but later began using them to circumvent sanctions.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Since 2020, Iran has required local bitcoin miners to sell bitcoin to the Central Bank of Iran, allowing the central bank to use it for imports.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Some constituent states and local governments also accept tax payments in bitcoin, including Colorado in the US and Zug and Lugano in Switzerland.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As of 2023, the US government owned more than $5 billion worth of seized bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As of 2018, the overwhelming majority of bitcoin transactions took place on cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Since 2014, regulated bitcoin funds also allow exposure to the asset or to futures as an investment.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin is used as a store of value: individuals and companies such as the Winklevoss twins and Elon Musk's companies SpaceX and Tesla have each bought and sold hundreds of millions of dollars worth of bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin wealth is highly concentrated, with 0.01% holding 27% of in-circulation currency, as of 2021.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] As of March 2025, El Salvador had $550 million worth of bitcoin in its international reserves, about 6,102 coins.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin, along with other cryptocurrencies, has been described as an economic bubble by several economists, including Nobel Prize in Economics laureates, such as Joseph Stiglitz, James Heckman, and Paul Krugman.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Another recipient of the prize, Robert Shiller, argues that bitcoin is rather a fad that may become an asset class.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] He describes its price growth as an "epidemic", driven by contagious narratives.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In 2024, Jean Tirole, also Nobel laureate, described bitcoin as a "pure bubble" as its intrinsic value is zero.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] According to him, some bubbles are long-lasting such as gold and fiat currencies, and it is impossible to predict whether bitcoin would implode like other financial bubbles or become an alternative to gold.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The same year, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell described bitcoin as a digital competitor to gold but not to the dollar as he argued it is a highly volatile speculative asset not used as a form of payment.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In 2025, Kenneth Rogoff claimed that Krugman was wrong and that Bitcoin had value as it is competing with the dollar to become the means of exchange of the underground economy which represents 20% of the world's GDP.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] According to Rogoff, bitcoin is "the ideal currency for a more fragmented and uncertain global landscape" and it could become appealing to emerging-market central banks as a "politically neutral" reserve currency.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] According to research published in the *International Review of Financial Analysis* in 2018, bitcoin as an asset is highly volatile and does not behave like any other conventional asset.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] According to one 2022 analysis published in *The Journal of Alternative Investments*, bitcoin was less volatile than oil, silver, US Treasuries, and 190 stocks in the S&P 500 during and after the 2020 stock market crash.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The term *hodl* was created in December 2013 for holding bitcoin rather than selling it during periods of volatility.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] In 2014, economist Nouriel Roubini described bitcoin as a Ponzi scheme.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Legal scholar Eric Posner disagrees, however, as "a real Ponzi scheme takes fraud; bitcoin, by contrast, seems more like a collective delusion".
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] A 2014 World Bank report also concluded that bitcoin was not a deliberate Ponzi scheme.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin markets operate 24 hours a day, seven days a week, contrasting with traditional financial markets that have fixed trading hours.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] Bitcoin prices show much higher volatility and respond strongly to both regulatory changes and market events.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The volume of bitcoin trading can fluctuate considerably among various exchanges and geographic regions.
[src:blockchain-mining/bitcoin] The daily transaction volume of bitcoin across all exchanges typically reaches $50 billion as of 2025.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] The **environmental impact of bitcoin** has been characterized in the literature as significant, particularly due to its energy use, greenhouse gas emissions, and electronic waste.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Bitcoin mining, the process by which bitcoins are created and transactions are finalized, is energy-consuming and results in carbon emissions.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] According to the 2025 Cambridge Digital Mining Industry Report, surveyed miners reported that 48% of their electricity came from fossil fuels and 52% from sustainable energy sources, including renewables and nuclear.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Moreover, bitcoins are mined on specialized computer hardware resulting in electronic waste.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] As of 2025, several empirical studies report an association between higher bitcoin-mining electricity use and worse environmental-sustainability indicators.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Bitcoin's environmental impact has attracted the attention of regulators, leading to incentives or restrictions in various jurisdictions.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2023 study in *ACS Sustainable Chemistry & Engineering* found potential economic benefits from using bitcoin mining at planned renewable-energy installations in the United States.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Bitcoin mining is a highly electricity-intensive proof-of-work process.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Miners run dedicated software to compete against each other and be the first to solve the current 10 minute block, yielding them a reward in bitcoins.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A transition to the proof-of-stake protocol, which has better energy efficiency, has been described as a sustainable alternative to bitcoin's scheme and as a potential solution to its environmental issues.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Bitcoin advocates oppose such a change, arguing that proof of work is needed to secure the network.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Bitcoin mining's distribution makes it difficult for researchers to identify the location of miners and electricity use.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] It is therefore difficult to translate energy consumption into carbon emissions.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Until 2021, most bitcoin mining was done in China.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Chinese miners relied on cheap coal power in Xinjiang and Inner Mongolia during late autumn, winter and spring, migrating to regions with overcapacities in low-cost hydropower (like Sichuan and Yunnan) between May and October.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] After China banned bitcoin mining in June 2021, its mining operations moved to other countries.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] By August 2021, mining was concentrated in the U.S.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] The shift from coal resources in China to coal resources in Kazakhstan increased bitcoin's carbon footprint, as Kazakhstani coal plants use hard coal, which has the highest carbon content of all coal types.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Despite the ban, covert mining operations gradually came back to China, reaching 21% of global hashrate as of 2022.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] As of 2025, a CCAF report based on a survey of 49 bitcoin-mining firms (about 48% of network hashrate at the time of data collection) reported their electricity mix as renewables (43%), natural gas (38%), nuclear (10%), and coal (9%).
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Analysis by the nonprofit tech company WattTime estimated that US miners consumed 54% fossil fuel-generated power.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] In 2023, Jamie Coutts, a crypto analyst writing for *Bloomberg Terminal*, said that renewables represented about half of global bitcoin mining sources.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A study in *Scientific Reports* found that from 2016 to 2021, each US dollar worth of mined bitcoin caused 35 cents worth of climate damage, compared to 95 for coal, 41 for gasoline, 33 for beef, and 4 for gold mining.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2025 paper published in *Nature Communications* found that the 34 largest U.S. bitcoin mines consumed 32.3 TWh of electricity from Aug 2022 to July 2023, 33% more than Los Angeles.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Fossil fuel power plants generated 85% of the increased electricity demand from these mines.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] The European Securities and Markets Authority and the European Central Bank suggested that using renewable energy for mining may limit the availability of clean energy for the general population.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2025 study in *Scientific Reports* of ten major cryptocurrency-producing countries (2019–2022) found that Bitcoin mining's electricity use was linked to worse environmental sustainability.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A larger share of renewables softened but did not eliminate these effects during the study period, and the impact on water use was limited.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2025 life-cycle assessment in *ACS Sustainable Chemistry & Engineering* quantified Bitcoin's carbon, water, and land footprints, concluding that the network's resource consumption poses sustainability challenges and highlighting the need for technological advances and cleaner energy sources.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] In 2018 *Nature Climate Change* published a study on projections of Bitcoin growth authored by Camilo Mora and fellow researchers from the University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Several subsequent papers contested the researchers' assumptions.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Mora and fellow publishers of the original article defended their paper.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] In a 2023 study published in *Ecological Economics*, researchers from the International Monetary Fund estimated that the global payment system represented about 0.2% of global electricity consumption, comparable to the consumption of Portugal or Bangladesh.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] For bitcoin, energy used is estimated around 500 kWh per transaction, compared to 0.001 kWh for credit cards (not including consumption from the merchant's bank, which receives the payment).
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] However, bitcoin's energy expenditure is not directly linked to the number of transactions.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Layer 2 solutions, like the Lightning Network, and batching, allow bitcoin to process more payments than the number of on-chain transactions suggests.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] For instance, in 2022, bitcoin processed 100 million transactions per year, representing 250 million payments.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] OECD notes that a direct comparison between blockchains, which are an infrastructure technology, and the energy consumption of financial sector activity may not be an appropriate comparison.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Bitcoins are usually mined on specialized computing hardware, called application-specific integrated circuits, with no alternative use beyond bitcoin mining.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Due to the consistent increase of the bitcoin network's hashrate, one 2021 study estimated that mining devices had an average lifespan of 1.3 years until they became unprofitable and had to be replaced, resulting in significant electronic waste.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] This study estimated bitcoin's annual e-waste to be over 30,000 tonnes (comparable to the small IT equipment waste produced by the Netherlands) and each transaction to result in 272 g (9.6 oz) of e-waste.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2024 systematic review criticized this estimate and argued, based on market sales and IPO data, that bitcoin mining hardware lifespan was closer to 4–5 years.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] According to the CCAF, e-waste is significantly lower, estimated at 2,300 tonnes in 2024 as 87% of hardware is recycled, sold or repurposed.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Field measurements around several large U.S. bitcoin mines show steady background sound in nearby residential areas commonly in the mid-30s to low-50s dBA, with higher levels closer to the mining facility.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2024 consultant study commissioned by Hood County, Texas, measured background levels ranging from 35–53 dBA and recorded a maximum around 59 dBA at two neighborhood locations, while measurements near the site ranged 60–65 dBA.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Separately, a 2022 *Washington Post* investigation that logged ~19,750 one-minute readings outside homes near a North Carolina cryptomine found sound levels above 55 dBA in 98% of readings and above 60 dBA in over 30% of readings.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Mitigation approaches reported by operators and consultants include acoustic barriers, equipment enclosures, optimized fan controls, and immersion cooling; however, effectiveness and adoption vary by site.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] According to a 2023 commentary in *Cell Reports Sustainability*, bitcoin's water footprint reached 1,600 gigalitres (5.7×1010 cu ft) in 2021, due to direct water consumption on site and indirect consumption from electricity generation.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] The author notes that this water footprint could be mitigated by using immersion cooling and power sources that do not require freshwater such as wind, solar, and thermoelectric power generation with dry cooling.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] As of 2025, an investigation by *The Texas Observer* reported that a bitcoin mining facility in Corpus Christi, Texas, used approximately 127,500 gallons of fresh water per day, based on municipal billing data.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2023 study in *Earth's Future* estimated the global land-use footprint attributable to bitcoin mining in 2020–2021 at 1,870 km2 (720 mi2), about 1.4 times the area of Los Angeles.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2025 study in *Nature Communications* found that the demand from 34 large U.S. bitcoin mines increased PM2.5 pollution and exposed about 1.9 million people to ≥0.1 μg/m3 additional PM2.5, sometimes far from the mines.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2024 review in *Environmental Research* linked proof-of-work mining to higher air pollution and potential health risks, calling for mitigation and better data.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2024 *JAMA* Viewpoint described potential community hazards from cryptocurrency mining, including air and noise pollution, and recommended protections for vulnerable groups.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] One 2020 paper found that, in 2018, each US$1 of bitcoin created was associated with about US$0.49 in combined health and climate damages in the United States (US$0.37 in China).
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2024 analysis estimated the climate and health damages from U.S. mining during 2019–2021 exceeded the value of coins generated in many geographic hotspots.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] In Western Pennsylvania, the bitcoin mining company Stronghold Digital Mining has described its use of waste coal to power bitcoin mining as environmental remediation.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Stronghold Digital Mining removes coal ash from abandoned coal mining sites to power their miners.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Coal ash is a form of coal waste that pollutes the groundwater and contains heavy metals.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] The Pennsylvania government provides tax credits to firms that are able to remove the hazardous waste.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Existing coal ash is highly combustible and prone to uncontrolled burning.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] The company collects the coal ash and processes it so it can be burned, which puts proportionately more Co2 into the atmosphere than burning clean coal would.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] The company reported removing 240,000 tons of waste in the second quarter of 2022, although the company was not profitable that quarter, and most of its profit was from selling energy back to the grid instead of from mining bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Rob Altenburg of PennFuture told WESA that using waste coal as fuel does not eliminate pollution, but shifts pollution from land and water to the air.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] In 2024, the environmental group Save Carbon County sued Stronghold Digital Mining and Pennsylvania, alleging that a bitcoin mine in northeastern Pennsylvania that burned waste coal and old tires for energy polluted nearby communities with mercury, sulfur dioxide, and other dangerous chemicals.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Bitcoin mining has also generated electricity from associated petroleum gas (APG), which is a methane-rich byproduct of crude oil drilling that is sometimes flared or released into the atmosphere, exacerbating the greenhouse gas effect.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Methane is a greenhouse gas with a global warming potential 28 to 36 times greater than CO2.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] One bitcoin mining company, Giga, placed a shipping container with thousands of bitcoin miners on an oil well and diverted the natural gas into generators that converted the gas into electricity which powered the miners.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] According to Crusoe Energy Systems, this reduces the green house gas emissions by 63% compared to continued flaring.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Environmental researcher Peter Howson disputed this framing saying that using flared methane for bitcoin mining can make fossil-fuel companies more profitable, slowing the transition to cleaner alternatives.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] According to a 2024 paper published in the *Journal of Cleaner Production*, bitcoin mining can finance methane mitigation of landfill gases.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Bitcoin mining has been proposed by advocates as a way to incentivize the expansion of clean energy operations.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] According to *Time* in 2022, most experts they had spoken with "dispute the idea that there has been any sort of boom in renewables due to crypto".
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] In a March 2022 article in *The New York Times*, David Yaffe-Bellany describes efforts within the industry to promote clean energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] This was in response to a backlash from environmentalists and the general public to the industry's increasing rate of carbon emissions.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] According to a 2023 paper in *ACS Sustainable Chemistry & Engineering,* bitcoin mining may offer opportunities to support the renewable-energy transition by using otherwise-curtailed renewable-energy and acting as a flexible electricity load.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2023 review published in *Resource and Energy Economics* also concluded that bitcoin mining could increase renewable capacity.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Another 2024 study by Fengqi You published in the *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America* showed that pairing green hydrogen infrastructure with bitcoin mining can accelerate the deployment of solar and wind power capacities.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] A 2024 study published in *Heliyon* simulated that a solar-powered bitcoin mining system could achieve a return on investment in 3.5 years compared to 8.1 years for selling electricity to the grid, while preventing 50,000 tons of CO2 emissions annually.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] The authors of the Heliyon study note note that proof-of-stake cryptocurrencies cannot provide these incentives.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] China's 2021 bitcoin mining ban was partly motivated by its role in illegal coal mining and environmental concerns.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] In September 2022, the US Office of Science and Technology Policy highlighted the need for increased transparency about electricity usage, greenhouse gas emissions, and e-waste.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] In November 2022, the US Environmental Protection Agency confirmed working on the climate impacts of cryptocurrency mining.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] In the US, New York State banned new fossil fuel mining plants with a two-year moratorium, citing environmental concerns, while Iowa, Kentucky, Montana, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Texas, and Wyoming encourage bitcoin mining with tax breaks.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] Texas incentives aim to cut methane emissions from flared gas using bitcoin mining.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] In January 2024, the US Energy Information Administration launched a mandatory survey of cryptocurrency miner energy use but suspended it one month later after it was successfully challenged by miners before the United States District Court for the Western District of Texas.
[src:blockchain-mining/environmental-impact-of-bitcoin] In October 2022, due to the global energy crisis, the European Commission invited member states to lower the electricity consumption of crypto-asset miners and end tax breaks and other incentives benefiting them.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] In the context of cryptocurrency mining, a **mining pool** is the pooling of resources by miners, who share their processing power over a network, to split the reward equally, according to the amount of work they contributed to the probability of finding a block.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] A "share" is awarded to members of the mining pool who present a valid partial proof-of-work.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Mining in pools began when the difficulty for mining increased to the point where it could take centuries for slower miners to generate a block.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] The solution to this problem was for miners to pool their resources so they could generate blocks more quickly and therefore receive a portion of the block reward on a consistent basis, rather than randomly once every few years.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Share is the principal concept of the mining pool operation.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] So it may be a block solution, but it is not necessarily so.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] For example, suppose a block solution is a number that ends with 10 zeros and, a share may be a number with 5 zeros at the end.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Sooner or later one of the shares will have not only 5, but 10 zeros at the end, and this will be the block solution.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Mining pools need shares to estimate the miner's contribution to the work performed by the pool to find a block.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] There are numerous miner reward systems: PPS, PROP, PPLNS, PPLNT, and many more.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Mining pools may contain hundreds or thousands of miners using specialized protocols.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] In all these schemes B stands for a block reward minus pool fee and p is a probability of finding a block in a share attempt ( $p=1/D$ , where D is current block difficulty).
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] A pool can support "variable share difficulty" feature, which means that a miner can select the share target (the lower bound of share difficulty) on their own and change p accordingly.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] The Pay-per-Share (PPS) approach offers an instant, guaranteed payout to a miner for their contribution to the probability that the pool finds a block.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Miners are paid out from the pool's existing balance and can withdraw their payout immediately.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] This model allows for the least possible variance in payment for miners while also transferring much of the risk to the pool's operator.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Each share costs exactly the expected value of each hash attempt $R=B\cdot p$ .
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Miners earn shares until the pool finds a block (the end of the mining round).
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] After that each user gets reward $R=B\cdot {\frac {n}{N}}$ , where n is amount of their own shares, and N is amount of all shares in this round.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] In other words, all shares are equal, but its value is calculated only at the end of each round.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Pooled mining (BPM), also known as "slush's system", due to its first use on a pool called "slush's pool', uses a system where older shares from the beginning of a block round are given less weight than more recent shares.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] A new round starts the moment the pool solves a block and miners are rewarded **Proportional** to the shares submitted.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] This reduces the ability to cheat the mining pool system by switching pools during a round, to maximize profit.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Pay-per-last-N-shares (PPLNS) method is similar to **Proportional**, but the miner's reward is calculated on a basis of N last shares, instead of all shares for the last round.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] This means that when a block is found, the reward of each miner is calculated based on the miner contribution to the last N pool shares.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Therefore, if the round was short enough all miners get more profit and vice versa.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Solo pools operate the same way as usual pools, with the only difference being that block reward is not distributed among all miners.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] The entire reward in a solo pool goes to the miner who finds the block.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Peer-to-peer mining pool (P2Pool) decentralizes the responsibilities of a pool server, removing the chance of the pool operator cheating or the server being a single point of failure.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Miners work on a side blockchain called a share chain, mining at a lower difficulty at a rate of one share block per 30 seconds.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Once a share block reaches the network target, it is transmitted and merged onto the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Miners are rewarded when this occurs proportional to the shares submitted prior to the target block.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] A P2Pool requires the miners to run a full node, bearing the weight of hardware expenses and network bandwidth.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Geometric Method (GM) was invented by Meni Rosenfeld.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] It is based on the same "score" idea, as Slush's method: the score granted for every new share, relatively to already existing score and the score of future shares, is always the same, thus there is no advantage to mining early or late in the round.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Generalized version of Geometric and PPLNS methods.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] It involves new parameter: o ("cross-round leakage").
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] When $o=0$ this becomes the Geometric method.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] When $o=1$ this becomes a variant of PPLNS, with exponential decay instead of a step function.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Usually, the blocks in the cryptocurrency network contain transactions.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Transaction fees are paid to the miner (mining pool).
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Different mining pools could share these fees between their miners or not.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Pay-per-last-N-shares (PPLNS), Pay-Per-Share Plus (PPS+) or Full Pay-Per-Share (FPPS) are the most fair methods where the payouts from the pool include not only the block subsidy but also the transaction fees.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Open-source monitoring tools allow public analysis of mining pool behavior, including hashrate distribution, block composition, and whether pools include the highest-fee transactions available in the mempool.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Block audit features compare expected block templates — generated using the same transaction selection algorithm as Bitcoin Core — against actual mined blocks.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Discrepancies may indicate transaction prioritization, transaction censorship, or out-of-band fee arrangements such as transaction acceleration services.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Multipools switch between different altcoins and constantly calculate which coin is at that moment the most profitable to mine.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Two key factors are involved in the algorithm that calculates profitability, the block time, and the price on the exchanges.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] To avoid the need for many different wallets for all possible minable coins, multipools may automatically exchange the mined coin to a coin that is accepted in the mainstream (for example bitcoin).
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Using this method, because the most profitable coins are being mined and then sold for the intended coin, it is possible to receive more coins in the intended currency than by mining that currency alone.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] This method also increases demand on the intended coin, which has the side effect of increasing or stabilizing the value of the intended coin.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Some companies that sell hash power may do so by aggregating the work of many small miners (for example, NiceHash), paying them proportionally by share like a pool would.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Some such companies operate their own pools.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] These can be considered multipools, because they usually employ a similar method of work switching, although the work they assign is determined by customer demand rather than "raw" profitability.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] When mining happens the miner simply "looks" through the pre-stored answers and submits the best one found to the network, with minimal energy used to read the hard drives.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] Due to the low hardware specification requirements of the PoC mining process, this type of mining can be conducted on a regular PC still being used for other day-to-day tasks.
[src:blockchain-mining/mining-pool] The first PoC blockchain was brought online in 2014 and is known as Signum today, with other PoC chains coming out much later, examples: Chia, Flax, and BitcoinHD.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Proof of work was later popularized by Bitcoin as a foundation for consensus in a permissionless decentralized network, in which miners compete to append blocks and mine new currency, each miner experiencing a success probability proportional to the computational effort expended.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] PoW and PoS (proof of stake) remain the two best known Sybil deterrence mechanisms.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] In the context of cryptocurrencies they are the most common mechanisms.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] A key feature of proof-of-work schemes is their asymmetry: the *work* – the computation – must be moderately hard (yet feasible) on the prover or requester side but easy to check for the verifier or service provider.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] This idea is also known as a CPU cost function, client puzzle, computational puzzle, or CPU pricing function.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Another common feature is built-in incentive-structures that reward allocating computational capacity to the network with value in the form of cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The purpose of proof-of-work algorithms is not proving that certain work was carried out or that a computational puzzle was "solved", but deterring manipulation of data by establishing large energy and hardware-control requirements to be able to do so.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Proof-of-work systems have been criticized by some environmentalists who argue that it generates externalities that are not reflected in market electricity prices which do not compensate for the economic and social benefits.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The interruptible load characteristics of proof-of-work mining provide demand-response services and support the integration of variable renewable energy under certain market and grid conditions.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The concept of Proof of Work (PoW) has its roots in early research on combating spam and preventing denial-of-service attacks.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] One of the earliest implementations of PoW was Hashcash, created by British cryptographer Adam Back in 1997.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] It was designed as an anti-spam mechanism that required email senders to perform a small computational task, effectively proving that they expended resources (in the form of CPU time) before sending an email.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] This task was trivial for legitimate users but would impose a significant cost on spammers attempting to send bulk messages.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Hashcash's system was based on the concept of finding a hash value that met certain criteria, a task that required computational effort and thus served as a "proof of work." The idea was that by making it computationally expensive to send large volumes of email, spamming would be reduced.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] One popular system, used in Hashcash, uses partial hash inversions to prove that computation was done, as a goodwill token to send an e-mail.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Whether PoW systems can actually solve a particular denial-of-service issue such as the spam problem is subject to debate; the system must make sending spam emails obtrusively unproductive for the spammer, but should also not prevent legitimate users from sending their messages.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] In other words, a genuine user should not encounter any difficulties when sending an email, but an email spammer would have to expend a considerable amount of computing power to send out many emails at once.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Proof-of-work systems are being used by other, more complex cryptographic systems such as Bitcoin, which uses a system similar to Hashcash.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Proof of work traces its theoretical origins to early efforts to combat digital abuse, evolving significantly over time to address security, accessibility, and broader applications beyond its initial anti-spam purpose.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The idea first emerged in 1993 as a deterrent for junk mail, but it was Satoshi Nakamoto’s 2008 whitepaper, "Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System," that solidified proof of work's potential as a cornerstone of blockchain networks.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] This development reflects the rising demands for secure, trustless systems.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The earliest appearance of proof of work was in 1993, when Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor proposed a system to curb junk email by requiring senders to perform computationally demanding tasks.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] In their paper, "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail," they outlined methods such as computing modular square roots, designed to be challenging to solve yet straightforward to verify, establishing a foundational principle of proof of work's asymmetry.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] This asymmetry is crucial to the effectiveness of proof of work, ensuring that tasks like sending spam are costly for attackers, while verification remains efficient for legitimate users.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] This conceptual groundwork found practical use in 1997 with Adam Back’s Hashcash, a system that required senders to compute a partial hash inversion of the SHA-1 algorithm, producing a hash with a set number of leading zeros.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Bitcoin, launched in 2009 by Satoshi Nakamoto, marked a pivotal shift by adapting Hashcash's proof of work for cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Nakamoto's Bitcoin whitepaper outlined a system using the SHA-256 algorithm, where miners compete to solve cryptographic puzzles to append blocks to the blockchain, earning rewards in the process.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Unlike Hashcash's static proofs, Bitcoin's proof of work algorithm dynamically adjusts its difficulty based on the average time taken to mine a block in the previous epoch, ensuring a consistent block time of approximately 10 minutes, creating a tamper-proof chain.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] This innovation transformed proof of work from a standalone deterrent into a consensus mechanism for a decentralized network, emphasizing financial incentives over computational effort.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Initially mined with standard CPUs, Bitcoin saw a rapid transition to GPUs, then to FPGAs and finally to ASICs, which vastly outperformed general hardware in solving SHA-256 puzzles.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] To address Bitcoin's increasing reliance on specialized hardware, Litecoin changed the Hashcash hash function from SHA-256 to Scrypt.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Developed by Colin Percival and detailed in the technical specification "The scrypt Password-Based Key Derivation Function," Scrypt was designed as a memory-intensive algorithm, requiring a moderate amount of RAM to compute.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Litecoin's goal of making mining more accessible to users with general-purpose hardware didn't last long, as mining followed a similar migration from CPUs through GPUs and FPGAs to ASICs.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] There are two classes of proof-of-work protocols.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Known-solution protocols tend to have slightly lower variance than unbounded probabilistic protocols because the variance of a rectangular distribution is lower than the variance of a Poisson distribution (with the same mean).
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] A generic technique for reducing variance is to use multiple independent sub-challenges, as the average of multiple samples will have a lower variance.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] There are also fixed-cost functions such as the time-lock puzzle.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Finally, some PoW systems offer **shortcut** computations that allow participants who know a secret, typically a private key, to generate cheap PoWs.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The rationale is that mailing-list holders may generate stamps for every recipient without incurring a high cost.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Whether such a feature is desirable depends on the usage scenario.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] At the IACR conference Crypto 2022 researchers presented a paper describing Ofelimos, a blockchain protocol with a consensus mechanism based on "proof of useful work" (PoUW).
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Rather than miners consuming energy in solving complex, but essentially useless, puzzles to validate transactions, Ofelimos achieves consensus while simultaneously providing a decentralized optimization problem solver.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The protocol is built around Doubly Parallel Local Search (DPLS), a local search algorithm that is used as the PoUW component.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The paper gives an example that implements a variant of WalkSAT, a local search algorithm to solve Boolean problems.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Optimisable proof of work (OPoW) is a variant of proof of work in which the proof-of-work algorithms themselves can be optimised without causing network instability or centralisation.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The mechanism incentivises two categories of participants: miners who compute solutions and are rewarded for adopting the most efficient algorithms, and algorithm contributors who develop and submit improved algorithms and earn rewards based on their adoption by miners.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] By decoupling the solving of computational problems from block creation, OPoW allows many solutions to be found per block, effectively creating a synthetic market for algorithms.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] In 2009, the Bitcoin network went online.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Bitcoin is a proof-of-work digital currency that, like Finney's RPoW, is also based on the Hashcash PoW.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] But in Bitcoin, double-spend protection is provided by a decentralized P2P protocol for tracking transfers of coins, rather than the hardware trusted computing function used by RPoW.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Bitcoin has better trustworthiness because it is protected by computation.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Bitcoins are "mined" using the Hashcash proof-of-work function by individual miners and verified by the decentralized nodes in the P2P Bitcoin network.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Since the creation of Bitcoin, proof-of-work has been the predominant design of peer-to-peer cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Studies have estimated the total energy consumption of cryptocurrency mining.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The PoW mechanism requires a vast amount of computing resources, which consume a significant amount of electricity.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] 2018 estimates from the University of Cambridge equate Bitcoin's energy consumption to that of Switzerland.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Each block that is added to the blockchain, starting with the block containing a given transaction, is called a confirmation of that transaction.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Ideally, merchants and services that receive payment in the cryptocurrency should wait for at least one confirmation to be distributed over the network, before assuming that the payment was done.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The more confirmations that the merchant waits for, the more difficult it is for an attacker to successfully reverse the transaction in a blockchain—unless the attacker controls more than half the total network power, in which case it is called a 51% attack.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Within the Bitcoin community there are groups working together in mining pools.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Some miners use application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) for PoW.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] This trend toward mining pools and specialized ASICs has made mining some cryptocurrencies economically infeasible for most players without access to the latest ASICs, nearby sources of inexpensive energy, or other special advantages.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Some PoWs claim to be ASIC-resistant, i.e. to limit the efficiency gain that an ASIC can have over commodity hardware, like a GPU, to be well under an order of magnitude.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] ASIC resistance has the advantage of keeping mining economically feasible on commodity hardware, but also contributes to the corresponding risk that an attacker can briefly rent access to a large amount of unspecialized commodity processing power to launch a 51% attack against a cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] By design, Bitcoin's Proof of Work consensus algorithm is vulnerable to Majority Attacks (51% attacks).
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Any miner with over 51% of mining power is able to control the canonical chain until their hash power falls below 50%.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] This allows them to reorg the blockchain, double-spend, censor transactions, and completely control block production.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] There was a notable double-spend on Bitcoin in March 2013 when the chain split due to a bug in the Bitcoin 0.8.0 client.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] While on the 0.8.0 chain, a merchant (OKPAY) confirmed a $10k deposit from a customer.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Bitcoin miners then 51% attacked the network, reverting 24 blocks and reversing the transaction leading to the customer's deposit.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The customer then double-spent the bitcoin on the canonical pre-0.8.0 chain as an experiment.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] A 2025 paper by Duke University Finance Professor Campbell Harvey estimates that a week-long 51% attack on Bitcoin could be executed with only $6 Billion at Oct 2025 prices.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The total cost of attack would be less than 1% of Bitcoin's total value.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] An attacker could profit from shorting Bitcoin or for non-economic reasons.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Bitcoin has asymmetric security where Bitcoin miners control its security, but they aren't the same people who hold Bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Unlike with Proof of Stake, there is much weaker economic incentive for those who control security to protect the network under Proof of Work.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Historically, many Proof of Work networks with low security budgets have fallen under 51% attacks., which highlights PoW's asymmetric security.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The amount of protection provided by PoW mining is close to the security budget of the network, which is roughly equal to the total block reward.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] With each additional halving, Bitcoin's security budget continues to fall relative to its market cap.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] In the past, Bitcoin developers were hopeful that transaction fees would rise to replace the declining block subsidy, but this has not been the case as transaction fees still only generate 1% of the total block reward.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] There are concerns that Bitcoin's security is unsustainable in the long run due to the declining security budget caused by its halvings.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Miners compete to solve crypto challenges on the bitcoin blockchain, and their solutions must be agreed upon by all nodes and reach consensus.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The solutions are then used to validate transactions, add blocks and generate new bitcoins.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Miners are rewarded for solving these puzzles and successfully adding new blocks.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] However, the Bitcoin-style mining process is very energy intensive because the proof of work is shaped like a lottery mechanism.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The underlying computational work has no other use but to provide security to the network that provides open access and has to work in adversarial conditions.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Miners have to use a lot of energy to add a new block containing a transaction to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] The energy used in this competition is what fundamentally gives Bitcoin its level of security and resistance to attacks.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Also, miners have to invest computer hardwares that need large spaces as fixed cost.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] In January 2022 vice-chair of the European Securities and Markets Authority Erik Thedéen called on the EU to ban the proof of work model in favor of the proof of stake model due its lower energy emissions.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] In November 2022 the state of New York enacted a two-year moratorium on cryptocurrency mining that does not completely use renewable energy as a power source for two years.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] Existing mining companies will be grandfathered in to continue mining without the use of renewable energy but they will not be allowed to expand or renew permits with the state.
[src:blockchain-mining/proof-of-work] No new mining companies that do not completely use renewable energy will be allowed to begin mining.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy systems have rapidly become more efficient and cheaper over the past 30 years.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] A large majority of newly installed worldwide electricity capacity is now renewable.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy sources, such as solar and wind power, have seen significant cost reductions over the past decade, making them more competitive with traditional fossil fuels.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In some geographic localities, photovoltaic solar or onshore wind is the cheapest new-build electricity.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] From 2011 to 2021, renewable energy grew from 20% to 28% of the global electricity supply.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Power from the sun and wind accounted for most of this increase, growing from a combined 2% to 10%.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Use of fossil energy shrank from 68% to 62%.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In 2024, renewables accounted for over 30% of global electricity generation and are projected to reach over 45% by 2030.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Many countries already have renewables contributing more than 20% of their total energy supply, with some generating over half or even all their electricity from renewable sources.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The main motivation to use renewable energy instead of fossil fuels is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, which cause climate change.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In general, renewable energy sources pollute much less than fossil fuels.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Renewables also cause much less air pollution than fossil fuels, improving public health, and are less noisy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The International Energy Agency estimates that to achieve net zero emissions by 2050, 90% of global electricity will need to be generated by renewables.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The current pace of renewable expansion remains far from this required rate globally, including in major economies with high financial capacities such as the G7 and the EU.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The deployment of renewable energy still faces obstacles, especially fossil fuel subsidies, lobbying by incumbent power providers, and local opposition to the use of land for renewable installations.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Like all mining, the extraction of minerals required for many renewable energy technologies also results in environmental damage.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Some also consider nuclear power a renewable power source, although this is controversial, as nuclear energy requires mining uranium, a nonrenewable resource.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] , are generating an increasing share of electricity.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Coal, oil, and natural gas remain the primary global energy sources even as renewables have begun rapidly increasing.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy is usually understood as energy harnessed from continuously occurring natural phenomena.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The International Energy Agency defines it as "energy derived from natural processes that are replenished at a faster rate than they are consumed".
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Solar power, wind power, hydroelectricity, geothermal energy, and biomass are widely agreed to be the main types of renewable energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy often displaces conventional fuels in four areas: electricity generation, hot water/space heating, transportation, and rural (off-grid) energy services.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Although almost all forms of renewable energy cause much fewer carbon emissions than fossil fuels, the term is not synonymous with low-carbon energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Some non-renewable sources of energy, such as nuclear power,generate almost no emissions, while some renewable energy sources can be very carbon-intensive, such as the burning of biomass if it is not offset by planting new plants.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy is also distinct from sustainable energy, a more abstract concept that seeks to group energy sources based on their overall permanent impact on future generations of humans.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] For example, biomass is often associated with unsustainable deforestation.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] As part of the global effort to limit climate change, most countries have committed to net zero greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In practice, this means phasing out fossil fuels and replacing them with low-emissions energy sources.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] This much needed process, coined as "low-carbon substitutions" in contrast to other transition processes including energy additions, needs to be accelerated multiple times in order to successfully mitigate climate change.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] At the 2023 United Nations Climate Change Conference, around three-quarters of the world's countries set a goal of tripling renewable energy capacity by 2030.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The European Union aims to generate 40% of its electricity from renewables by the same year.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy is more evenly distributed around the world than fossil fuels, which are concentrated in a limited number of countries.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] It also brings health benefits by reducing air pollution caused by the burning of fossil fuels.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The potential worldwide savings in health care costs have been estimated at trillions of dollars annually.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The two most important forms of renewable energy, solar and wind, are *intermittent energy sources*: they are not available constantly, resulting in lower capacity factors.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In contrast, fossil fuel power plants, nuclear power plants and hydropower are usually able to produce precisely the amount of energy an electricity grid requires at a given time.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Solar energy can only be captured during the day, and ideally in cloudless conditions.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Wind power generation can vary significantly not only day-to-day, but even month-to-month.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] This poses a challenge when transitioning away from fossil fuels: energy demand will often be higher or lower than what renewables can provide.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In the medium-term, this variability may require keeping some gas-fired power plants or other dispatchable generation on standby until there is enough energy storage, demand response, grid improvement, or base load power from non-intermittent sources.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In the long-term, energy storage is an important way of dealing with intermittency.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Using diversified renewable energy sources and smart grids can also help flatten supply and demand.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Sector coupling of the power generation sector with other sectors may increase flexibility: for example the transport sector can be coupled by charging electric vehicles and sending electricity from vehicle to grid.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Similarly the industry sector can be coupled by hydrogen produced by electrolysis, and the buildings sector by thermal energy storage for space heating and cooling.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Building overcapacity for wind and solar generation can help ensure sufficient electricity production even during poor weather.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In optimal weather, it may be necessary to curtail energy generation if it is not possible to use or store excess electricity.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Electrical energy storage is a collection of methods used to store electrical energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Electrical energy is stored during times when production (especially from intermittent sources such as wind power, tidal power, solar power) exceeds consumption, and returned to the grid when production falls below consumption.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Pumped-storage hydroelectricity accounts for more than 85% of all grid power storage.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Batteries are increasingly being deployed for storage and grid ancillary services and for domestic storage.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Green hydrogen is a more economical means of long-term renewable energy storage, in terms of capital expenditures compared to pumped hydroelectric or batteries.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Two main renewable energy sources - solar power and wind power - are usually deployed in distributed generation architecture, which offers specific benefits and comes with specific risks.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Notable risks are associated with centralisation of 90% of the supply chains in a single country (China) in the photovoltaic sector.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Similar attacks have targeted wind power farms through vulnerabilities in their remote control and monitoring systems.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The European NIS2 directive partially responds to these challenges by extending the scope of cybersecurity regulations to the energy generation market.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Recent analyses indicate that global solar photovoltaic capacity surpassed 1 terawatt in 2024, providing about 6–7% of global electricity supply.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy infrastructure is also increasingly vulnerable to extreme weather events linked to climate change, such as heat waves, wildfires, severe storms, and flooding.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Solar farms can experience reduced output during prolonged heat or smoke conditions, while wind turbines may require shutdowns during high-wind events or face damage from icing or wave action.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] These climate-related stresses can threaten the continuity of electricity supply in regions with high shares of variable renewables.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] As a result, governments and grid operators are adopting climate-resilience standards, hardening infrastructure, and developing emergency-response protocols to maintain energy security under more frequent and severe weather conditions.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Solar power produced around 1.3 terrawatt-hours (TWh) worldwide in 2022, representing 4.6% of the world's electricity.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Almost all of this growth has happened since 2010.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Solar energy can be harnessed anywhere that receives sunlight; however, the amount of solar energy that can be harnessed for electricity generation is influenced by weather conditions, geographic location and time of day.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] There are two mainstream ways of harnessing solar energy: solar thermal, which converts solar energy into heat; and photovoltaics (PV), which converts it into electricity.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] PV is far more widespread, accounting for around two thirds of the global solar energy capacity as of 2022.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] It is also growing at a much faster rate, with 170 GW newly installed capacity in 2021, compared to 25 GW of solar thermal.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Passive solar refers to a range of construction strategies and technologies that aim to optimize the distribution of solar heat in a building.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Examples include solar chimneys, orienting a building to the sun, using construction materials that can store heat, and designing spaces that naturally circulate air.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] From 2020 to 2022, solar technology investments almost doubled from US$162 billion to US$308 billion, driven by the sector's increasing maturity and cost reductions, particularly in solar photovoltaic (PV), which accounted for 90% of total investments.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] China and the United States were the main recipients, collectively making up about half of all solar investments since 2013.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Despite reductions in Japan and India due to policy changes and COVID-19, growth in China, the United States, and a significant increase from Vietnam's feed-in tariff program offset these declines.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Globally, the solar sector added 714 gigawatts (GW) of solar PV and concentrated solar power (CSP) capacity between 2013 and 2021, with a notable rise in large-scale solar heating installations in 2021, especially in China, Europe, Turkey, and Mexico.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In 2023, global solar power capacity grew by nearly 30%, driven by falling panel prices and expanded government incentives worldwide.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] A photovoltaic system, consisting of solar cells assembled into panels, converts light into electrical direct current via the photoelectric effect.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] PV systems range from small, residential and commercial rooftop or building integrated installations, to large utility-scale photovoltaic power station.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] A household's solar panels can either be used for just that household or, if connected to an electrical grid, can be aggregated with millions of others.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The first utility-scale solar power plant was built in 1982 in Hesperia, California by ARCO.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The plant was not profitable and was sold eight years later.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] However, over the following decades, PV cells became significantly more efficient and cheaper.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] As a result, PV adoption has grown exponentially since 2010.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Global capacity increased from 230 GW at the end of 2015 to 890 GW in 2021.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] PV grew fastest in China between 2016 and 2021, adding 560 GW, more than all advanced economies combined.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In 2025, four of the ten biggest solar power stations were in China, including the biggest, Talatan Solar Park.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Solar panels are recycled to reduce electronic waste and create a source for materials that would otherwise need to be mined, but such business is still small and work is ongoing to improve and scale-up the process.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Unlike photovoltaic cells that convert sunlight directly into electricity, solar thermal systems convert it into heat.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] They use mirrors or lenses to concentrate sunlight onto a receiver, which in turn heats a water reservoir.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The heated water can then be used in homes.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The advantage of solar thermal is that the heated water can be stored until it is needed, eliminating the need for a separate energy storage system.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Solar thermal power can also be converted to electricity by using the steam generated from the heated water to drive a turbine connected to a generator.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] However, because generating electricity this way is much more expensive than photovoltaic power plants, there are very few in use today.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Floatovoltiacs, or floating solar panels, are solar panels floating on bodies of water.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] There are both positive and negative points to this.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Some positive points are increased efficiency and price decrease of water space compared to land space.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] A negative point is that making floating solar panels could be more expensive.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Agrivoltaics is where there is simultaneous use of land for energy production and agriculture.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] There are again both positive and negative points.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] A positive viewpoint is there is a better use of land, which leads to lower land costs.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] A negative viewpoint is it the plants grown underneath would have to be plants that can grow well under shade, such as Polka Dot Plant, Pineapple Sage, and Begonia.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Agrivoltaics not only optimizes land use and reduces costs by enabling dual revenue streams from both energy production and agriculture, but it can also help moderate temperatures beneath the panels, potentially reducing water loss and improving microclimates for crop growth.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] However, careful design and crop selection are crucial, as the shading effect may limit the types of plants that can thrive, necessitating the use of shade-tolerant species and innovative management practices.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Humans have harnessed wind energy since at least 3500 BC.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Until the 20th century, it was primarily used to power ships, windmills and water pumps.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Today, the vast majority of wind power is used to generate electricity using wind turbines.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Modern utility-scale wind turbines range from around 600 kW to 9 MW of rated power.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The power available from the wind is a function of the cube of the wind speed, so as wind speed increases, power output increases up to the maximum output for the particular turbine.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Areas where winds are stronger and more constant, such as offshore and high-altitude sites, are preferred locations for wind farms.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Wind-generated electricity met nearly 4% of global electricity demand in 2015, with nearly 63 GW of new wind power capacity installed.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Wind energy was the leading source of new capacity in Europe, the US and Canada, and the second largest in China.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In Denmark, wind energy met more than 40% of its electricity demand while Ireland, Portugal and Spain each met nearly 20%.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Globally, the long-term technical potential of wind energy is believed to be five times total current global energy production, or 40 times current electricity demand, assuming all practical barriers needed were overcome.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] This would require wind turbines to be installed over large areas, particularly in areas of higher wind resources, such as offshore, and likely also industrial use of new types of VAWT turbines in addition to the horizontal axis units currently in use.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] As offshore wind speeds average ~90% greater than that of land, offshore resources can contribute substantially more energy than land-stationed turbines.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Investments in wind technologies reached US$161 billion in 2020, with onshore wind dominating at 80% of total investments from 2013 to 2022.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Offshore wind investments nearly doubled to US$41 billion between 2019 and 2020, primarily due to policy incentives in China and expansion in Europe.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Global wind capacity increased by 557 GW between 2013 and 2021, with capacity additions increasing by an average of 19% each year.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Since water is about 800 times denser than air, even a slow flowing stream of water, or moderate sea swell, can yield considerable amounts of energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Water can generate electricity with a conversion efficiency of about 90%, which is the highest rate in renewable energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Much hydropower is flexible, thus complementing wind and solar, as it not intermittent.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In 2021, the world renewable hydropower capacity was 1,360 GW.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Only a third of the world's estimated hydroelectric potential of 14,000 TWh/year has been developed.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] New hydropower projects face opposition from local communities due to their large impact, including relocation of communities and flooding of wildlife habitats and farming land.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] High cost and lead times from permission process, including environmental and risk assessments, with lack of environmental and social acceptance are therefore the primary challenges for new developments.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] It is popular to repower old dams thereby increasing their efficiency and capacity as well as quicker responsiveness on the grid.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Where circumstances permit existing dams such as the Russell Dam built in 1985 may be updated with "pump back" facilities for pumped-storage which is useful for peak loads or to support intermittent wind and solar power.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Because dispatchable power is more valuable than VRE countries with large hydroelectric developments such as Canada and Norway are spending billions to expand their grids to trade with neighboring countries having limited hydro.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Biomass is biological material derived from living, or recently living organisms.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Most commonly, it refers to plants or plant-derived materials.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] As an energy source, biomass can either be used directly via combustion to produce heat, or converted to a more energy-dense biofuel like ethanol.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Wood is the most significant biomass energy source as of 2012 and is usually sourced from a trees cleared for silvicultural reasons or fire prevention.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Municipal wood waste – for instance, construction materials or sawdust – is also often burned for energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The biggest per-capita producers of wood-based bioenergy are heavily forested countries like Finland, Sweden, Estonia, Austria, and Denmark.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Bioenergy can be environmentally destructive if old-growth forests are cleared to make way for crop production.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In particular, demand for palm oil to produce biodiesel has contributed to the deforestation of tropical rainforests in Brazil and Indonesia.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In addition, burning biomass still produces carbon emissions, although much less than fossil fuels (39 grams of CO2 per megajoule of energy, compared to 75 g/MJ for fossil fuels).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Some biomass sources are unsustainable at current rates of exploitation (as of 2017).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Biofuels are primarily used in transportation, providing 3.5% of the world's transport energy demand in 2022, up from 2.7% in 2010.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Biojet is expected to be important for short-term reduction of carbon dioxide emissions from long-haul flights.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Aside from wood, the major sources of bioenergy are bioethanol and biodiesel.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Bioethanol is usually produced by fermenting the sugar components of crops like sugarcane and maize, while biodiesel is mostly made from oils extracted from plants, such as soybean oil and corn oil.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Most of the crops used to produce bioethanol and biodiesel are grown specifically for this purpose, although used cooking oil accounted for 14% of the oil used to produce biodiesel as of 2015.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The biomass used to produce biofuels varies by region.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Maize is the major feedstock in the United States, while sugarcane dominates in Brazil.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In the European Union, where biodiesel is more common than bioethanol, rapeseed oil and palm oil are the main feedstocks.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] China, although it produces comparatively much less biofuel, uses mostly corn and wheat.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In many countries, biofuels are either subsidized or mandated to be included in fuel mixtures.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] There are many other sources of bioenergy that are more niche, or not yet viable at large scales.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] For instance, bioethanol could be produced from the cellulosic parts of crops, rather than only the seed as is common today.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Sweet sorghum may be a promising alternative source of bioethanol, due to its tolerance of a wide range of climates.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] There is also a great deal of research involving algal fuel, which is attractive because algae is a non-food resource, grows around 20 times faster than most food crops, and can be grown almost anywhere.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Geothermal energy is thermal energy (heat) extracted from the Earth's crust.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] It originates from several different sources, of which the most significant is slow radioactive decay of minerals contained in the Earth's interior, as well as some leftover heat from the formation of the Earth.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Some of the heat is generated near the Earth's surface in the crust, but some also flows from deep within the Earth from the mantle and core.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Geothermal energy extraction is viable mostly in countries located on tectonic plate edges, where the Earth's hot mantle is more exposed.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] As of 2023, the United States has by far the most geothermal capacity (2.7 GW, or less than 0.2% of the country's total energy capacity), followed by Indonesia and the Philippines.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Geothermal energy can be either used directly to heat homes, as is common in Iceland where almost all of its energy is renewable, or to generate electricity.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Iceland is a global leader in renewable energy, relying almost entirely on its abundant geothermal and hydroelectric resources derived from volcanic activity and glaciers.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] At smaller scales, geothermal power can be generated with geothermal heat pumps, which can extract heat from ground temperatures of under 30 °C (86 °F), allowing them to be used at relatively shallow depths of a few meters.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Electricity generation requires large plants and ground temperatures of at least 150 °C (302 °F).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In some countries, electricity produced from geothermal energy accounts for a large portion of the total, such as Kenya (43%) and Indonesia (5%).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Technical advances may eventually make geothermal power more widely available.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] For example, enhanced geothermal systems involve drilling around 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) into the Earth, breaking apart hot rocks and extracting the heat using water.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In theory, this type of geothermal energy extraction could be done anywhere on Earth.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] There are also other renewable energy technologies that are still under development, including enhanced geothermal systems, concentrated solar power, cellulosic ethanol, piezoelectricity, and marine energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] These technologies are not yet widely demonstrated or have limited commercialization.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Some may have potential comparable to other renewable energy technologies, but still depend on further breakthroughs from research, development and engineering.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Enhanced geothermal systems (EGS) are a new type of geothermal power which does not require natural hot water reservoirs or steam to generate power.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Most of the underground heat within drilling reach is trapped in solid rocks, not in water.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] EGS technologies use hydraulic fracturing to break apart these rocks and release the heat they contain, which is then harvested by pumping water into the ground.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The process is sometimes known as "hot dry rock" (HDR).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Unlike conventional geothermal energy extraction, EGS may be feasible anywhere in the world, depending on the cost of drilling.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] EGS projects have so far primarily been limited to demonstration plants, as the technology is capital-intensive due to the high cost of drilling.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Sand batteries are large tanks filled with soapstone that absorb heat.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Excess heat energy from renewable energy is piped into the tank and then energy is discharged as boiling water, steam, or heated air.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Finland is using this technology in Pornainen as Polar Night Energy built a 1MW sand battery that can store up to 100 MWh that went online in 2025.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Piezoelectricity is the conversion of existing mechanical stress or vibration (classical mechanics) into an electrical charge without consuming or depleting a fuel source.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Piezotronics enables the interaction of piezoelectric and semiconducting behaviors to modulate energy barriers at contact surface, thereby controlling charge carrier transport.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Since the introduction of nanogenerators, the efficiency of microscale energy harvesting has improved.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] For instance, nanogenerators typically consist of piezoelectric nanowires; as these wires bend or compress, the applied mechanical stress causes the ions within the material's crystal lattice to shift their positions.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] This shift disrupts the nanowire's charge symmetry which causes an instantaneous charge polarization (separation of positive and negative charges) across the nanowire's ends.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Once polarized, electrons are freed from the attached electrode which generates usable alternating current (AC) electricity that can energize low-power sensors.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Piezoelectric microelectromechanical systems (piezoMEMS), such as actuators for artificial organs and pacemakers or micropumps for drug delivery and reagent transfers, are vital for medical purposes and energy harvesting.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Furthermore, specialized components like piezoelectric resonators and quartz crystal oscillators are used to regulate electrical circuit frequencies.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Marine energy (also sometimes referred to as ocean energy) is the energy carried by ocean waves, tides, salinity, and ocean temperature differences.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Technologies to harness the energy of moving water include wave power, marine current power, and tidal power.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Reverse electrodialysis (RED) is a technology for generating electricity by mixing fresh water and salty sea water in large power cells.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Most marine energy harvesting technologies are still at low technology readiness levels and not used at large scales.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Tidal energy is generally considered the most mature, but has not seen wide deployment.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The world's largest tidal power station is on Sihwa Lake, South Korea, which produces around 550 gigawatt-hours of electricity per year.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Earth emits roughly 1017 W of infrared thermal radiation that flows toward the cold outer space.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Solar energy hits the surface and atmosphere of the earth and produces heat.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Using various theorized devices like emissive energy harvester (EEH) or thermoradiative diode, this energy flow can be converted into electricity.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In theory, this technology can be used during nighttime.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Producing liquid fuels from oil-rich (fat-rich) varieties of algae is an ongoing research topic.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Various microalgae grown in open or closed systems are being tried including some systems that can be set up in brownfield and desert lands.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] There have been numerous proposals for space-based solar power, in which very large satellites with photovoltaic panels would be equipped with microwave transmitters to beam power back to terrestrial receivers.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] A 2024 study by the NASA Office of Science and Technology Policy examined the concept and concluded that with current and near-future technologies it would be economically uncompetitive.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Collection of static electricity charges from water droplets on metal surfaces is an experimental technology that would be especially useful in low-income countries with relative air humidity over 60%.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The high fuel-efficiency of breeder reactors could greatly reduce concerns about fuel supply, energy used in mining, and storage of radioactive waste.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] With seawater uranium extraction (currently too expensive to be economical), there is enough fuel for breeder reactors to satisfy the world's energy needs for 5 billion years at 1983's total energy consumption rate, thus making nuclear energy effectively a renewable energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] In addition to seawater the average crustal granite rocks contain significant quantities of uranium and thorium with which breeder reactors can supply abundant energy for the remaining lifespan of the sun on the main sequence of stellar evolution.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Artificial photosynthesis uses techniques including nanotechnology to store solar electromagnetic energy in chemical bonds by splitting water to produce hydrogen and then using carbon dioxide to make methanol.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] However, prominent research faces hurdles, Sun Catalytix a MIT spin-off stopped scaling up their prototype fuel-cell in 2012 because it offers few savings over other ways to make hydrogen from sunlight.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Recent research emphasizes that while artificial photosynthesis shows promise in splitting water to generate hydrogen, its broader significance lies in the ability to produce dense, carbon-based solar fuels suitable for transport applications, such as aviation and long-haul shipping.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] These fuels, if derived from carbon dioxide and water using sunlight, could close the carbon loop and reduce reliance on fossil-based hydrocarbons.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] However, realizing this potential requires overcoming major technical hurdles, including the development of efficient, durable catalysts for water oxidation and CO2 reduction, and careful attention to land use and public perception.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Global energy consumption in 2019 was approximately 65 petawatt-hours (PWh) per year or 65,000 terawatt-hours (TWh) annually.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] According to a comprehensive peer-reviewed study published in 2023, the technical potentials for utility-scale solar photovoltaic, concentrated solar power, onshore wind, and offshore wind each exceed 100 PWh/year, and thus each of them is capable of meeting the Humankind's total demand *in theory*.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Technical Potential: Over 5,800 PWh per year from solar PV alone using current technology.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] This represents approximately 89 times current global energy demand.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Thus, utilizing only 2% of the solar power can solve Humankind's energy problems, in principle.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Technical Potential: Nearly 900 PWh per year from onshore and offshore wind combined, in kilowatts: 900,000,000,000,000 kWh/year (900 trillion kWh/year).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] This represents approximately 14 times current global energy demand.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] However, it is highly intermittent, and it is not feasible to cover most of the earth surface to collect all wind.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] With current technology, at least 6,700 PWh per year can be captured from solar and wind, which is more than 100 times global energy demand.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Gross Theoretical Potential: Approximately 52 PWh/year distributed over 11.8 million potential locations worldwide.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] This equals to about 33% of annually required energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Conventional Geothermal: Technical potential above 10 PWh/year.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Enhanced Geothermal Systems (EGS): About 600 terawatts (TW) of geothermal capacity using thermal resources within 8 km of depth, equivalent to about 4,000 PWh of technical potential for annual generation.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The full technical potential of next-generation geothermal systems is sufficient to meet global electricity demand 140 times over and is second only to solar PV among renewable technologies.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Rooftop Solar PV, Wave, and Tidal: Technical potentials above 1 PWh/year each.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Ocean Thermal Energy Conversion (OTEC): Technical potential above 10 PWh/year.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] Salinity Gradient: Technical potential above 0.1 PWh/year.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] When including all renewable energy sources, the global technical potential ranges from 164 to 27,200 PWh/year, which is 6.6 to 1,101 times the 2021 electricity consumption of 24.7 PWh/year.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] The literature assessing the global economic potential of renewables shows that the economic potential is higher than current and near-future electricity demand.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p01] More specifically: Around 60% of the world's solar resource and 15% of its wind resource is already economically competitive compared with local fossil fuel generation.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Most new renewables are solar, followed by wind then hydro then bioenergy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Investment in renewables, especially solar, tends to be more effective in creating jobs than coal, gas or oil.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Worldwide, renewables employ about 12 million people as of 2020, with solar PV being the technology employing the most at almost 4 million.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] However, as of February 2024, the world's supply of workforce for solar energy is lagging greatly behind demand as universities worldwide still produce more workforce for fossil fuels than for renewable energy industries.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In 2021, China accounted for almost half of the global increase in renewable electricity.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] There were 3,146 gigawatts installed in 135 countries, while 156 countries have laws regulating the renewable energy sector.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The International Renewable Energy Agency reported that during 2025 renewables accounted for 85.6% of new electricity generation capacity globally, with solar photovoltaics providing nearly three-quarters of the increase.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] At the end of 2025, renewables constituted 49.4% of global installed electricity generating capacity.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Globally in 2020 there are over 10 million jobs associated with the renewable energy industries, with solar photovoltaics being the largest renewable employer.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The clean energy sectors added about 4.7 million jobs globally between 2019 and 2022, totaling 35 million jobs by 2022.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Some studies say that a global transition to 100% renewable energy across all sectors – power, heat, transport and industry – is feasible and economically viable.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] One of the efforts to decarbonize transportation is the increased use of electric vehicles (EVs).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Despite that and the use of biofuels, such as biojet, less than 4% of transport energy is from renewables.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Occasionally hydrogen fuel cells are used for heavy transport.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Meanwhile, in the future electrofuels may also play a greater role in decarbonizing hard-to-abate sectors like aviation and maritime shipping.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Solar water heating makes an important contribution to renewable heat in many countries, most notably in China, which now has 70% of the global total (180 GWth).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Most of these systems are installed on multi-family apartment buildings and meet a portion of the hot water needs of an estimated 50–60 million households in China.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Worldwide, total installed solar water heating systems meet a portion of the water heating needs of over 70 million households.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Heat pumps provide both heating and cooling, and also flatten the electric demand curve and are thus an increasing priority.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Renewable thermal energy is also growing rapidly.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] About 10% of heating and cooling energy is from renewables.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA) stated that ~86% (187 GW) of renewable capacity added in 2022 had lower costs than electricity generated from fossil fuels.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] IRENA also stated that capacity added since 2000 reduced electricity bills in 2022 by at least $520 billion, and that in non-OECD countries, the lifetime savings of 2022 capacity additions will reduce costs by up to $580 billion.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Investment: Companies, governments and households have committed increasing amounts to decarbonization, including renewable energy (solar, wind), electric vehicles and associated charging infrastructure, energy storage, energy-efficient heating systems, carbon capture and storage, and hydrogen.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The countries most reliant on fossil fuels for electricity vary widely on how great a portion of that electricity is generated from renewables, leaving wide variation in renewables' growth potential.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] With increasingly widespread implementation of renewable energy sources, costs have declined, most notably for energy generated by solar panels.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] (LCOE) is a measure of the average net present cost of electricity generation for a generating plant over its lifetime.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] with 62% of total renewable power generation added in 2020 having lower costs than the cheapest new fossil fuel option.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] ": Trend of costs and deployment over time, with steeper lines showing greater cost reductions as deployment progresses.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] This was an increase of over three and possibly four times the equivalent amount invested in the decade of 2000–2009 (no data is available for 2000–2003).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] As of 2022, an estimated 28% of the world's electricity was generated by renewables.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] By the end of 2024, global renewable power capacity reached 4,300 gigawatts (GW), with solar photovoltaics accounting for over 60% of annual additions.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] UK-based think tank Ember reported that wind and solar combined generated more electricity than gas globally in a month for the first time in April 2026.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Solar and wind power are scaling up faster than previous sources of electricity.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Declining costs, modular design, and improved battery storage help the transition to renewable energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In 2023, electricity generation from wind and solar sources was projected to exceed 30% by 2030.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] A December 2022 report by the IEA forecasts that over 2022–2027, renewables are seen growing by almost 2,400 GW in its main forecast, equal to the entire installed power capacity of China in 2021.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] This is an 85% acceleration from the previous five years, and almost 30% higher than what the IEA forecast in its 2021 report, making its largest ever upward revision.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Renewables are set to account for over 90% of global electricity capacity expansion over the forecast period.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] To achieve net zero emissions by 2050, IEA believes that 90% of global electricity generation will need to be produced from renewable sources.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] REPowerEU, the EU plan to escape dependence on fossil Russian gas, is expected to call for much more green hydrogen.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] After a transitional period, renewable energy production is expected to make up most of the world's energy production.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In 2018, the risk management firm, DNV GL, forecasts that the world's primary energy mix will be split equally between fossil and non-fossil sources by 2050.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Middle eastern nations are also planning on reducing their reliance fossil fuel.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Many planned green projects will contribute in 26% of energy supply for the region by 2050 achieving emission reductions equal to 1.1 Gt CO2/year.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In July 2014, the WWF and the World Resources Institute convened a discussion among a number of major US companies who had declared their intention to increase their use of renewable energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] These discussions identified a number of "principles" which companies seeking greater access to renewable energy considered important market deliverables.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] These principles included choice (between suppliers and between products), cost competitiveness, longer term fixed price supplies, access to third-party financing vehicles, and collaboration.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In some locations, individual households can opt to purchase renewable energy through a consumer green energy program.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Renewable energy in developing countries is an increasingly used alternative to fossil fuel energy, as these countries scale up their energy supplies and address energy poverty.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Renewable energy technology was once seen as unaffordable for developing countries.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] However, since 2015, investment in non-hydro renewable energy has been higher in developing countries than in developed countries, and comprised 54% of global renewable energy investment in 2019.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The International Energy Agency forecasts that renewable energy will provide the majority of energy supply growth through 2030 in Africa and Central and South America, and 42% of supply growth in China.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Most developing countries have abundant renewable energy resources, including solar energy, wind power, geothermal energy, and biomass, as well as the ability to manufacture the relatively labor-intensive systems that harness these.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] By developing such energy sources developing countries can reduce their dependence on oil and natural gas, creating energy portfolios that are less vulnerable to price rises.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In many circumstances, these investments can be less expensive than fossil fuel energy systems.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In Kenya, the Olkaria V Geothermal Power Station is one of the largest in the world.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The Grand Ethiopia Renaissance Dam project incorporates wind turbines.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Once completed, Morocco's Ouarzazate Solar Power Station is projected to provide power to over a million people.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Policies to support renewable energy have been vital in their expansion.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Where Europe dominated in establishing energy policy in the early 2000s, most countries around the world now have some form of energy policy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA) is an intergovernmental organization for promoting the adoption of renewable energy worldwide.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] It aims to provide concrete policy advice and facilitate capacity building and technology transfer.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] IRENA was formed in 2009, with 75 countries signing the charter of IRENA.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] As of April 2019, IRENA has 160 member states.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The then United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon has said that renewable energy can lift the poorest nations to new levels of prosperity.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The 2015 Paris Agreement on climate change motivated many countries to develop or improve renewable energy policies.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In 2017, a total of 121 countries adopted some form of renewable energy policy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] National targets that year existed in 176 countries.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In addition, there is also a wide range of policies at the state/provincial, and local levels.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Some public utilities help plan or install residential energy upgrades.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Many national, state and local governments have created green banks.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] A green bank is a quasi-public financial institution that uses public capital to leverage private investment in clean energy technologies.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Green banks use a variety of financial tools to bridge market gaps that hinder the deployment of clean energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] China's count of multi-country patent filings has surged since the mid-2010s, leading in batteries and solar, though Europe still dominates in wind energy and smart grids.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] China also leads in highly cited publications in global peer-reviewed journals.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The International Renewable Energy Agency's (IRENA) 2023 report on renewable energy finance highlights steady investment growth since 2018: USD 348 billion in 2020 (a 5.6% increase from 2019), US$430 billion in 2021 (24% up from 2020), and US$499 billion in 2022 (16% higher).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] This trend is driven by increasing recognition of renewable energy's role in mitigating climate change and enhancing energy security, along with investor interest in alternatives to fossil fuels.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Policies such as feed-in tariffs in China and Vietnam have significantly increased renewable adoption.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Furthermore, from 2013 to 2022, installation costs for solar photovoltaic (PV), onshore wind, and offshore wind dropped by 69%, 33%, and 45%, respectively, making renewables more cost-effective.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Between 2013 and 2022, the renewable energy sector underwent a significant realignment of investment priorities.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Investment in solar and wind energy technologies markedly increased.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In contrast, other renewable technologies such as hydropower (including pumped storage hydropower), biomass, biofuels, geothermal, and marine energy experienced a substantial decrease in financial investment.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Notably, from 2017 to 2022, investment in these alternative renewable technologies declined by 45%, falling from US$35 billion to US$17 billion.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In 2023, the renewable energy sector experienced a significant surge in investments, particularly in solar and wind technologies, totaling approximately US$200 billion—a 75% increase from the previous year.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The increased investments in 2023 contributed between 1% and 4% to the GDP in key regions including the United States, China, the European Union, and India.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The energy sector receives investments of approximately US$3 trillion each year, with US$1.9 trillion directed towards clean energy technologies and infrastructure.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] To meet the targets set in the Net Zero Emissions (NZE) Scenario by 2035, this investment must increase to US$5.3 trillion per year.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Whether nuclear power should be considered a form of renewable energy is an ongoing subject of debate.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Legal definitions of renewable energy usually exclude nuclear energy technologies, with the notable exception of the U.S. state of Utah.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Dictionary-sourced definitions of renewable energy technologies often omit or explicitly exclude mention of nuclear energy sources, with an exception made for the natural nuclear decay heat generated within the Earth.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The most common fuel used in conventional nuclear fission power stations, uranium-235 is "non-renewable" according to the United States' Energy Information Administration, the organization, however, is silent on the recycled MOX fuel.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The National Renewable Energy Laboratory does not mention nuclear power in its "energy basics" definition.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In 1987, the Brundtland Commission (WCED) classified fission reactors that produce more fissile nuclear fuel than they consume (breeder reactors, and if developed, fusion power) among conventional renewable energy sources, such as solar power and hydropower.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The monitoring and storage of radioactive waste products is also required upon the use of other renewable energy sources, such as geothermal energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The geopolitical impact of the growing use of renewable energy is a subject of ongoing debate and research.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Many countries wealthy in oil, such as Qatar, Russia, Saudi Arabia and Norway, and are able to exert diplomatic or geopolitical influence as a result of their oil.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Most of these countries are expected to be among the geopolitical "losers" of the energy transition, although some, like Norway, are also significant producers and exporters of renewable energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Fossil fuels and the infrastructure to extract them may, in the long term, become stranded assets.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] It has been speculated that countries dependent on fossil fuel revenue may one day find it in their interests to quickly sell off their remaining fossil fuels.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Conversely, nations abundant in renewable resources, and the minerals required for renewables technology, are expected to gain influence.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In particular, China has become the world's dominant manufacturer of the technology needed to produce or store renewable energy, especially solar panels, wind turbines, and lithium-ion batteries.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Nations rich in solar and wind energy could become major energy exporters.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Some may produce and export green hydrogen, although electricity is projected to be the dominant energy carrier in 2050, accounting for almost 50% of total energy consumption (up from 22% in 2015).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Countries with large uninhabited areas such as Australia, China, and many African and Middle Eastern countries have a potential for huge installations of renewable energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The production of renewable energy technologies requires rare-earth elements with new supply chains.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Countries in Africa with already weak governments that rely on fossil fuel revenue may face even higher political instability or popular unrest.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Analysts consider Nigeria, Angola, Chad, Gabon, and Sudan, all countries with a history of military coups, to be at risk of instability due to dwindling oil income.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] A study found that transition from fossil fuels to renewable energy systems reduces risks from mining, trade and political dependence because renewable energy systems don't need fuel – they depend on trade only for the acquisition of materials and components during construction.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] European Commission President Ursula von der Leyen said that Europe is "too reliant" on natural gas and too dependent on natural gas imports.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Energy transition can also improve a country's energy security and energy independence, mitigating impacts from fossil fuel markets or geopolitical pressure from oil producers.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The proliferation of renewable energy could also weaken petrostates' trading power and their global influence.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] As the world becomes more electrified, renewable technologies will be embedded into the national economies of various markets, especially developing countries, removing the leverage petrostates have on the global energy structure.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The transition to renewable energy requires increased extraction of certain metals and minerals.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Like all mining, this impacts the environment and can lead to environmental conflict.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Wind power requires large amounts of copper and zinc, as well as smaller amounts of the rarer metal neodymium.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Solar power is less resource-intensive, but still requires significant amounts of aluminum.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The expansion of electrical grids requires both copper and aluminum.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Batteries, which are critical to enable storage of renewable energy, use large quantities of copper, nickel, aluminum and graphite.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Demand for lithium is expected to grow 42-fold from 2020 to 2040.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Demand for nickel, cobalt and graphite is expected to grow by a factor of about 20–25.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] For each of the most relevant minerals and metals, its mining is dominated by a single country: copper in Chile, nickel in Indonesia, rare earths in China, cobalt in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), and lithium in Australia.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] China dominates processing of all of these.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Recycling these metals after the devices they are embedded in are spent is essential to create a circular economy and ensure renewable energy is sustainable.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] By 2040, recycled copper, lithium, cobalt, and nickel from spent batteries could reduce combined primary supply requirements for these minerals by around 10%.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] A controversial approach is deep sea mining.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Minerals can be collected from new sources like polymetallic nodules lying on the seabed.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] This would damage local biodiversity, but proponents point out that biomass on resource-rich seabeds is much scarcer than in the mining regions on land, which are often found in vulnerable habitats like rainforests.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Due to co-occurrence of rare-earth and radioactive elements (thorium, uranium and radium), rare-earth mining results in production of low-level radioactive waste.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Installations used to produce wind, solar and hydropower are an increasing threat to key conservation areas, with facilities built in areas set aside for nature conservation and other environmentally sensitive areas.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] They are often much larger than fossil fuel power plants, needing areas of land up to 10 times greater than coal or gas to produce equivalent energy amounts.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] More than 2000 renewable energy facilities are built, and more are under construction, in areas of environmental importance and threaten the habitats of plant and animal species across the globe.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The authors' team emphasized that their work should not be interpreted as anti-renewables because renewable energy is crucial for reducing carbon emissions.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The key is ensuring that renewable energy facilities are built in places where they do not damage biodiversity.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In 2020 scientists published a world map of areas that contain renewable energy materials as well as estimations of their overlaps with "Key Biodiversity Areas", "Remaining Wilderness" and "Protected Areas".
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The authors assessed that careful strategic planning is needed.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Climate change is making weather patterns less predictable.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] This can seriously hamper the use of renewable energy.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Nuclear energy is also affected as drought creates water shortage, so nuclear power plants sometimes do not have enough water for cooling.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] say countries should back renewable energy to fight climate change.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The same survey a year later shows that renewable energy is considered an investment priority in the European Union, China and the United States.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Solar power plants may compete with arable land, while on-shore wind farms often face opposition due to aesthetic concerns and noise.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Such opponents are often described as NIMBYs ("not in my back yard").
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Some environmentalists are concerned about fatal collisions of birds and bats with wind turbines.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Although protests against new wind farms occasionally occur around the world, regional and national surveys generally find broad support for both solar and wind power.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Community-owned wind energy is sometimes proposed as a way to increase local support for wind farms.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] A 2011 UK Government document stated that "projects are generally more likely to succeed if they have broad public support and the consent of local communities.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] This means giving communities both a say and a stake." In the 2000s and early 2010s, many renewable projects in Germany, Sweden and Denmark were owned by local communities, particularly through cooperative structures.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In the years since, more installations in Germany have been undertaken by large companies, but community ownership remains strong in Denmark.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Prior to the development of coal in the mid 19th century, nearly all energy used was renewable.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The oldest known use of renewable energy, in the form of traditional biomass to fuel fires, dates from more than a million years ago.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The use of biomass for fire did not become commonplace until many hundreds of thousands of years later.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The second oldest usage of renewable energy was probably harnessing the wind in order to drive ships over water.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] This practice can be traced back some 7000 years, to ships in the Persian Gulf and on the Nile.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Geothermal energy from hot springs has been used for bathing since Paleolithic times and space heating since ancient Roman times.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Moving into the time of recorded history, the primary sources of traditional renewable energy were human labor, animal power, water power, wind, in grain crushing windmills, and firewood, a traditional biomass.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Max Weber mentioned the end of fossil fuel in the concluding paragraphs of his Die protestantische Ethik und der Geist des Kapitalismus (The Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Capitalism), published in 1905.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Development of solar engines continued until the outbreak of World War I.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The importance of solar energy was recognized in a 1911 *Scientific American* article: "in the far distant future, natural fuels having been exhausted [solar power] will remain as the only means of existence of the human race".
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] The theory of peak oil was published in 1956.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In the 1970s environmentalists promoted the development of renewable energy both as a replacement for the eventual depletion of oil, as well as for an escape from dependence on oil, and the first electricity-generating wind turbines appeared.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Solar had long been used for heating and cooling, but solar panels were too costly to build solar farms until 1980.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] New government spending, regulation and policies helped the renewables industry weather the 2008 financial crisis and the Great Recession better than many other sectors.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] In 2022, renewables accounted for 30% of global electricity generation, up from 21% in 1985.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Water mills (Ancient China and Ancient Persia).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Traditional cooling and ventilation systems based on windcatchers and Solar updraft tower (or Solar chimney).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Traditional architecture aware of natural heat transfer and natural energy transformation processes.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Using animal biomass in ancient fuel bricks.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Solar ovens and furnaces in ancient China, India, Egypt, and Persia.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Solar energy applications for traditional agricultural processing (drying), engineering material properties (solar curing of pottery and ceramics), and ancient health practices (natural disinfection by solar radiation).
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Long-distance gravitational water flow control in ancient qanat technology for water transport and supply.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Cargo and passenger transportation using sails on rivers, seas, and oceans.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Cargo and passenger transportation based on understanding water currents in rivers, seas, and oceans.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Using renewable vegetation (such as desert shrubs, agricultural waste, and pruned branches) for producing light and heat.
[src:blockchain-mining/renewable-energy-p02] Using renewable oils (vegetable or animal-based) for producing light and heat.
